                  </hi>, and <persName id="def22-2116-18350921" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def22-2116-18350921" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def22-2116-18350921" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def22-2116-18350921" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN SMITH</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18350921-2116-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350921-2116-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="miscellaneous"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350921-2116-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="conspiracy"></interp> a conspiracy.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BUMPUS</hi>, <hi rend="italic">with</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. WHITEHEAD</hi>, <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">BALL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1177" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1177" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1177" type="surname" value="BRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1177" type="given" value="AARON"></interp>AARON BRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a horse-dealer, and live in Red-lion-yard, Hol<lb></lb>born. On the 8th of June I started two omnibuses, to run from Paddington, in Middlesex, to the Bank—I took out two licenses, Nos. 348 and 349—they ran from Paddington along Oxford-street and Holborn—at that time, Thomas Bolton, James Bardell, Joseph Bardell, Richard Bird, Thomas Bird, Richard Carpenter, William Cowderoy, James Hill, Joseph Johnson,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210198"></xptr>
               <p>John Newell, Samuel Pearce, Josiah Parkes, philip sellick, and Robert Trevett had omnibuses on that road—my omnibuses started between nine and ten o'clock in the morning, from Paddington—on the first day, I was watching to see my omnibuses come down Holborn, and there were two or three omnibuses with each, hunting them, and driving them on as fast as they could; Trevett's and Bolton's omnibuses in particular, and Mr. Bird's also—I believe there was no other that day—I watched them several other days, and saw them drive close up to he pavement, and drive their poles close up to my omnibns, so that no passenger could get in—on those other days I saw the omnibuses belonging to the other defendants I have named doing so—I do not know that there was one who has not done so—the whole of them have been a continual annoyance—on the 15th, I lengthened one of my omnibuses to Maida—hill, still continuing on the same line of road, through Paddington—on that day, a new omnibus, called "The Emperor," No. 352, with the name of "Edmund Sylvester" on it, started against the one of mine, which ran to Maida—hill; and another, called "The Albion," No. 177, with the name of "Thomas Corbett" on it, started in opposition to the one of mine, which went to Paddington—John Sylvester drove the "Emperor, "and John Smith was the conductor; but whether they did so the first day it started, I cannot tell—Gough drove the "Albion," and one of the Trevett's, (Thomas, I think,) was the conductor—I had observed Cow<lb></lb>deroy driving his omnibus the first week, which he every now and then does drive—he was one who ran his pole up against me, and put me on one side, and was annoying me—I saw the other defendants in the first week; and omnibuses would come down from Paddington to where I set out, wait till I came out of my yard, follow my omnibuses up to Paddington, wait till they turned round to go, and then immediately gallop close before them—one day, one of my horses came home with the wheel run over his foot—sometimes there was a pannel broken—I saw Sylvester's omnibus run against my pannel one day in Oxford-street—I have seen them come fol<lb></lb>lowing my <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> home, without plying for hire; and they would stop for an hour, to see whether we attempted to go out again—this was done frequently, every day almost—about three weeks after we started, there came a very rainy day—one of my <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> let water—we took the passengers out, and put them in another <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—I got into the bus that let water, and made them drive it down to the maker's in Whitechapel; and the "Emperor" followed me all the way, and stopped there four hours—John Sylvester drove the "Emperor" there, and John Smith was the conductor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever meet any of the defendants any where? <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Yes; the first I saw of them was Josiah Parkes—I forget when it was but it was near the beginning of my starting—I found him in my yard in Holborn, when I got there, we went into the public-house, and had a glass of brandy-and-water—he told me I was a madman to start if I did not buy times—that the "Pad<lb></lb>dington committee" would run me off the road, and ruin me—I said no, I should try—I alterwards saw Trevett, Hill, and Cowderoy, all three together, I think it was on the 4th of July—I had just come home from the bazaar, and got out of the <hi rend="italic">bus,</hi> when Robert Trevett came, laid hold of my coat, and said I should go and have something to drink—I said I had not had my dinner, and I seldom took any thing before dinner—he said, would I come back—I said I would—I went back, and Trevett, Hill, and Cowderoy were there, drinking—they asked me whether I meant to do what was rights—I said I meant to stop if I could, and keep on my omnibus they said it</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210199"></xptr>
               <p>was no use, for their committee was so strong it was no use for one to op<lb></lb>pose them—It would cost them about 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week each man, and it would cost me 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to oppose them, and if I could afford to stand the loss of that I had better stop—I said, "Never mind that, I shall stop as long as I can"—Cowderoy said, "Why don't you buy times, and belong to us?"—I said I never would belong to any committee of that kind while I lived—I would stop, if I could, and Cowderoy said, "Ah, do, old one, start half a dozen, that will soon end it"—they got drinking very hard, and got warm with liquor, but nothing more passed about the omnibuses, except that I should be sure to be ruined; and Hill said, "He is an old one, and has been amongst us many years; we must let him in some how or another"—Cowde<lb></lb>roy said, "Why don't you sell him your times?" and Hill said, "I will take five hundred guineas for them"—my son was there at that time—I left them to go home—Hill ran over the road, caught hold of me, and said they had been standing treat to me, and I must to them—I said I wanted no more, but I would give him a glass of brandy-and-water—we went, and Joseph Bardell came to the door—we went out, and spoke to him in the street—he said, "It is of no use your going against this committee; they will ruin you as sure as you are born; go and buy somebody's time"—he said they were such b----y <hi rend="italic">out-and-outers,</hi> they would beat anybody, and even if Mr. Horne, or the greatest stage—master in London were to start against the Paddington committee, they would be sure to be beaten—he said, "Hill, why don't you sell him your times?"—Hill said, "I did offer them to him a little while age at five hundred guineas, but I won't take six hundred for them now"—my son was not present at that time—I had no further conversation with Bardell and Hill that night, but I have seen Bardell frequently—he told me they would be sure to best me—they would have nobody there but what belonged to the committee, and bought times—he said he belonged to the committee, but did not often go—Robert Trevett has called upon me three or four times—he has told me it was no use my running, they would suffer no one on the road except they pur<lb></lb>chased times—he said I had better purchase times, or I should be ruined—they had ruined several, and they would ruin me—Bolton has called upon me three or four times, and had the same conversation, but he ad<lb></lb>vised me at one time to go to Kentish—town—I made a reply that I did not like Kentish—town, as the turnpikes were heavy—he said the turn-pikes should not cost me much, as he was proprietor of the gates—he said it was no use my attempting to go against so many of them, that they paid but a trific a week in, and there was such a body of them it was foolish of any one individual going against so many of them—I do not recollect having any conversation with any of the other defendants—I run on and was losing a great deal of money, till I called a sale at Mr. Allen's, in St. Martin's, on Wednesday, the 29th of July—my omnibuses stopped for that sale on Sunday night the 26th—the other omnibuses continued with me—they came dowm on Saturday morning, the 25th, and followed me all day long—they seldom came on a Sunday—I did not see them on the Monday—my sale took place on Wednesday—I sold five horses—my omnibuses were only on bire—on the Thursday my Paddington one went out again—the de<lb></lb>fendants' omnibuses were out that day, but I did not see them—on the Friday I saw the "Emperor" and the "Albion" follow my one <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—they <hi rend="italic">tuco'd</hi> him, as they call it, all day, one before and the other behind—selveaterdrove the "Emperor," and I believe Gough drove the "Albion"—I started my other omnibus on the 2nd of August—the other omnibus still</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210200"></xptr>
               <p>continued to pursue me in the same way as before, or rather worse, as they supposed I was beaten, and they set too with more vengeance against me—one of my omnibuses is on still—the other ceased running on the 30th of August—the whole of this book is not in my handwriting, but I see it every day of my life, either night or morning—It contains the earnings of each bus—I have seen John Sylvester up at Paddington two or three times—he has said, "It is a pity you should go on so; why don't you come and buy time? they will never let you have any time without you come and buy time"—Smith joined in the same conversation—neither of them told me who employed them, but I have seen the same horses working in the "Emperor," and then in Mr. Bolton's omnibuses—and the horses worked in the Albion" in Mr. Trevett's—I have been a horse-dealer thirty-six or thirty-seven years, and have been unfortunate twice.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What is your name? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Aaron Bray; I am not a Jew—I was never in the omnibus trade till the 8th of June—I had been a hackney-coach and <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> propritor—I put on two omnibuses—they had no name in particular. but my own name at full length on them—I employed James Raimes, John Lee, henry Mann, and Thomas Travett—I did not know that either of them had been in the ser<lb></lb>vice of Robert Trevett, nor do I know it now—they were recommaded to me by a person at Paddington as proper persons to drive my omnibuses—I have heard, since Thomas Trevett has left me, that he is a cousin of Robert Trevetts, and that they had had some words—but I did not hear that he had been in his employment—I knew there was a person of the name of Trevett on the road—I do not know that I ever heard that he had been Trevett's employ—I do not know what Raines had been before he came to my employ—I heard that he had been a pugilist—I have not heard that he had been concerned in a manslaughter case—I never went much into the <hi rend="italic">ring</hi>—I was at a fight some years ago—I have been twice a bankrupt—the last time was the latter end of last year or the beginning of this—the first time was about seven years ago—I never compounded with my creditors, nor pro<lb></lb>posed to do so—I never gave my drivers any particular directions what to do—they asked me, when they came recommanded to me by Mr. David<lb></lb>son, of Paddington, at what time they should come, and where they should go—I said, "Go where you like; I know nothing about the times; you know the business better than I do"—I never gave directions to Lee to keep close to Trevett, or to any one—they said so and so was a good time, giving me the hours, and I said very well—they said, "A quarter be<lb></lb>fore ten and two are as good times as you can go;" and I said, "Go at those times"—I knew nothing about whose times they were—I never knew who went at seven, eight, nine, or any other hour.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever tell Lee or Mann to stick close to Trevett's omnibus? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never in my life to stick close to any omnibus—I do not know Mr. Carr, a hatter, who keeps a shop opposite Day and Martin's—I do not re<lb></lb>collect being at a hatter's shop opposite Day and martin's, on White<lb></lb>Tuesday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever use this expression, that you had begun the opposition, and you would stick close to the old thief, Trevett, and take a little of the <hi rend="italic">bounce</hi> out of him, let it cost what it would? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never in my life—I know budd, the timekeeper at the Bank—I never said in his presence that I would ran against the old cobler and melt his wax—Trevett taxed me with that—he said he had heard from his nepher that I had said those</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210201"></xptr>
               <p>words—I never gave my men orders to go in any times, nor to stick close to Trevett's omnibuses, because his times were good times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long is it since your first bankruptcy? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About seven years—I was then a horse-dealer, and in the same yard which I now keep—I purchased the premises about three months afterwards—they took bills for them at different dates—my first divident was 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; there was another about 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and there will be ano<lb></lb>ther—I will swear that more than 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. has been paid—my second bank<lb></lb>ruptey was at the latter end of 1834—there has been no dividend declared on that as yet—It is in the hands of Mr. Green—I cannot tell what my cre<lb></lb>ditors will get—Hill asked me to give 500 guineas to buy time—I dare say he knew I was a bankrupt—when a man is unfortunate it is generally known—I hava had conversation with a person of the name of Bardell, the brother of the two Bardells who are indicated—he is a vetrinary surgeon, and a very respectable man—he asked me how I came to indict them—I said it was my attorney's advice, and I could not go from it—my attorney is Mr. Norton—he advised me to indict the Bardells—I went with Mr. Bardell to Mr. Norton's, and there was a conversation about their putting in bail. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Now Mr. Bardell is alive, and is here; do you remember his asking Mr. Norton why he advised you to put his two brothers into the indict<lb></lb>ment, when they were innocent? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not recollect it—Mr. Norton might have dropped such an expression as, That he was determined they should not be witness for the other defendants—It was not in my presence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean that such a villanous expression might be used, and you forget it; such an infamous expression? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Mr. Norton's answer was, "we have no occasion to press the indictment against your brothers"—Mr. Bardell went on to say something about the bail, and Mr. Norton said, "The indictment has no occassion to be pressed against your brothers; they have not much to fear; but you must put in bail"—he said that after advising me to include them in the indictment.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was any thing said about a hundred pounds? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never to me, or to Mr. Bardell in my presence, upon my oath; nor did Mr. Norton say that he put the Bardells into the indictment that they should not be wit<lb></lb>nesses, nor anything to that effect—Mr. Norton did not tell me why he put the Bardells in the indictment—I went to him to indict the Paddington committee, and he indicted whom he pleased—I appointed with Mr. Bar<lb></lb>dell to meet him at Mr. Norton's—I went there to meet him—he got there first.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Norton say that their names must remain in the indict<lb></lb>ment; his object was to prevent their being witnesses; because, if they were ommitted, the paddington proprietors would subpœna them against Bray? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never, sir; nor that their evidence would be of importance, I having commissioned Joseph Bardell to raise 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to take my omni<lb></lb>buses iff the road, and discontinue further opposition; and if he could not get 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., to take 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and they to take my stock at a valuation—there was not a word said about it—we were there half an hour, talking about the indictment a little, but the most was about putting in bail.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Upon your oath. was not the appointment to go to Norton with Bar<lb></lb>dell to try to get his brothers out of the indictment? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; the agree<lb></lb>ment was for Mr. Norton not to oppose the bail, but take them on Mon<lb></lb>day—there was nothing said about getting his brothers out of the indict<lb></lb>ment—I never in any way wanted money to settle this business.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210202"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Nonton say in Mr. Bardell's presence, that if the proprietors did not consent to your proposition, he would ruin Bolton, Pearee, Bird, and Trevett, or he would have his heart out and his limbs broken? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No: Bardell was not desired to ask his brothers if the proprietors would come to terms—I saw Mann this morning—I do not know whether he is a wit<lb></lb>ness for me—he is one of the persons who complained that he was hunted—I never gave Mann directions to drive against Bolton—not any person—I do not know this man (<hi rend="italic">looking at a man named Archer</hi>)—I never saw him before, to my knowledge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever say to your conductor, in Archer's presence, "Go on wwith that omnibus (<hi rend="italic">pointing to one</hi>), and stick to him; I will have the shirt off his back before I have done with him?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never in my life—I know Parish, the policeman, No. 45—I never had any conversation with him about this—I do not know that ever he was obliged to lead my omni<lb></lb>bus out of the way—I know No. 7 has—I never spoke to him in the Poultry about my opposition, to my knowledge—I know a person named Alexander—I have no recollection of mentioning the name of Alexander to Parish.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you recollect his saying that you could not expect the people would let you take the bread out of their months withour giving you some trouble? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I think I have heard such words, but I think it was from No. 7, not from Parish.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you say, "I should have been very well off, if Alexander had not put me in the hold?" A. I said I should have been better off if Alexander had come out with me, as he promised—I possibly might say we should have made the Paddington masters look about them—I have been summoned two or three times by the police for causing an obstruction—I have heard of the names of Colson and Wilson as time-keepers—I have seen Colson, and spoken to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you ever said this in his presence, That unless you could receive 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from the proprietors, you would indict them all fro a conspi<lb></lb>racy, and ruin them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never in my life to any soul—I remember two of Trevett's mem being taken into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you remember using this expression, in the presence of Colson, that you had been as good as your word; it was not the men you wished to hurt, as you could get nothing out of them, but their masters, and that the law must take its course, unless you were paid 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to take your omnibus off?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never, to any man upon earth—I have spoken to Bates, the policeman, No. 7—he has summoned my driver two or three times fro obstructing the road and he summoned me twice, once was for taking time at the Bank—he said I should not take time—my man got off by paying 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I was summoned to Marlborough-street—one of Mr. Bol<lb></lb>ton's omnibuses ran against mine—my son got into a gallop, and they were both <hi rend="italic">had up</hi>—It is the men that are summoned, but the master always at<lb></lb>tends, and if they are fined he pays it—I know Bates has often told me of my men doing wrong—I said, "Then summons them, I have nothing to do with it; I have spoken to my men about it, and they said they did no such thing"—I cannot tell whether Mann is here—I have not subpœnaed him—I was not afraid that he would tell the jury that I ordered him to drive against Bolton—I never said so—nor about getting 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I know the policeman, No. 13—I do not know his name—I recollect his having two persons in custody one night at the Mansion-house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you say on that occasion, this, or any thing like this—that you</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210203"></xptr>
               <p>would have all the omnibuses removed from the Bank; and you would be d----d if you did not line the street with <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>, if it cost you five hundred pounds? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never—I mean distinctly to swear I never used to that man any such expression, but I remember his having the men very unlawfully taken up—their words were taken to come on Monday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> About how many witnesses have been subpœnaed by Mr. Norton in this case? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A great many—I have heard fifty or sixty—there were only four witnesses went before the Grand Jury and only two of them were heard—the amount of debts at my first bankruptey was about 5000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 6000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and the second time not 1500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I have not paid fifteen shillings in the pound on either commission.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you aware that, not having paid 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., you are not in point of law, entitled to any property? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, Sir—I succeeded to my stable in about three months after my first commission—I never left it the second time—It was mortgaged to my bankers, and they let me remain.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was Thomas Bird a creditor under your second commission? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not that I know of—I do not know the man—I have no recollection of his name for a penny—I never got into his debt—I had some bills of exchange out, but very few—I have no recollection of Bird's name in either of my bankrupteies, or in any kind of dealing—I did not enter a bill of Bird's for a backney-coach—I have no recollection of it—I hired my omni<lb></lb>buses of Mr. Boswell, in Aldgate High-street—I set them up on the 8th of June—I paid part of the hire of them 17<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., having had them twelve weeks—I had my <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> ordered before Alexander had any idea of coming out—he then told me he was coming out—I did not agree with him to bring out omnibuses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did you mean by saying just now, if he had come out as he agreed? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, Sir, "as he said he would," I did expect him to come out with me, and I thought he was coming out on that day, but I heard after<lb></lb>wards the Paddington committee had given him 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., to stop him—I consulted with Mr. Norton a very little time after I started, I believe about three weeks—he had been my attorney before—I have heard that forty or fifty omnibuses ran from the Bank to Paddington before I set up; but I do not know.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not state in your own yard, to Mr. John Bardell, that you did not wish to indict the Bardells at all, but your lawyer said they must be in the indictment as he had a reason for it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I said I had no animosity against them—I did not say I did not wish to indict them at all—I told them Mr. Norton said they must be in the indictment, he had a cause for putting them in—I did not say I did not know the rea<lb></lb>son, but if he would meet me at Mr. Norton's I would go and see if I could not get them out—I did not go to Mr. Norton's for any such pur<lb></lb>pose—I went to Mr. Norton's on a Sunday, with Mr. John Bardell—I do not recollect his asking Mr. Norton why he had put his brothers in the in<lb></lb>dictment—I will swear it was not said in my presence—I do not recollect Mr. Norton being questioned as to whether they could not get out of it—there was very little said—we were not there ten minutes—I will swear I did not hear Mr. Norton say their names must remain in the indict<lb></lb>ment his object being to preven their being witnesses for the defence—I will swear I never heard it; nor that their evidence against them would be of importance.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you ever said to any body that you would have times or 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.?</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210204"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never in my life—I did not know the different times when I started—I had John Lee in my service, and William Beales.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not direct both Lee and Beales to run in oppsition to Bind and Johnson, and nut to leave them till they had your orders, if they did not earn one shilling? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never—I belive they have been in every one's time, but I never gave them order's except not to go in the women's time, (there are some female properties)—that was about a month or five weeks before the prosecution commenced.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you not sworn to Mr. Phillips that you never gave them any specific directions at all, but that they ran when they pleased, and did as they liked? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, they did—I have never, on any occasion, directly or indirectly, by myself or Mr. Nortson, sought or agreed to settle this matter if I could get money paid me—I did not, after the 8th of June, give direc<lb></lb>tions to Lee to run my omnibus against Bird and Johnson.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KNOWLES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know Thomas Parker? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; he is foreman to Mr. Aldridge—I might see him about the 5th of this month, with the two Bardells, and there might be a conversation about this indictment—I told them I had no animosity against them, but their names must be in the indictment.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> You were a bankrupt the first time, about seven years ago? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I obtained my certificate about two months after<lb></lb>wards—I did not leave my premises—they took bills at certain dates, which were afterwards paid—the second time I was a bankrupt, was about ten months ago—I had lost 900<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. in three weeks, by bad debts, which was the case of my being a bankrupt—I got my certificate on the 15th of January—every one of my creditors signed it, who had proved—I do not know where Lee or Mann live—I live nearly oppsite Day and Martin's, within a few doors—I hardly know what the meaning of a time is—I understand it is to start three minitues before another—If my omnibus started from the Bank at ten o'clock in the morning, it would go to Padding<lb></lb>ton, and it would stop there for half perhaps—they went just as they could—that would necessarily interfere with different times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Tell us every thing that was said by you to John Bardell? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He asked me if I would go with him to get Mr. Norton to take the bail for his brother, without some certificate, or something; I forget what; and would I go and advise Mr. Norton to do so, without giving any trouble; and I did so—he did not ask me why the Bardells were made defendants—when I went with him he complained of Mr. Norton having refused the bail, and asked whether, if he were there on Monday, prepared with the bail, he would take it; and 1 told Mr. Norton not give them any more trouble, but to take their bail—I did not want to be litigious ducting himself wrong to my <hi rend="italic">buses.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1178" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1178" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1178" type="surname" value="BRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1178" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT BRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's son. On the 8th of June, my father commenced running two omnibuses, Nos. 348 and 349—I have been coachman to both of them—I began about three weeks after they started, but I was repeatedly with them before—I rode on horseback with them—the drivers of the other omnibuses tried to oppose us and to injure us, by pulling up against us—they would cross us and go before our <hi rend="italic">buses,</hi> and their conductors would jump down, if passengers bailed us, to get them away from our <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>—the names of the present defendants were on those omnibuses—Bolton had five on the stones, Bardells, 1 think, had four, Richard Bird had two, Thomas Bird had two, Carpenter had two, Cowderoy had sometimes five sometimes six, Hill had two, I believe—John<lb></lb>son,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210205"></xptr>
               <p>I think, had three, Newell had three, Pearce had three, Parkes had three or four, Sellick had three, and Trevett two—they were all run<lb></lb>ning on the road before the 15th of June, and it was them which so annoyed us—on the 15th of June, the "Albion" and the "Emperor," op<lb></lb>position omnibuses, were put on—I cannot exactly remember who was the coachman of the "Albion," but John Gulliver drove it, and when he did not, some odd man did; George Dodd was the conductor; John Gough has driven it, and Trevent been the conductor—I do not know his christian name—I believe it is Robert—the name on the "Albion" was Thomas Corbett, No. 177, and on the "Emperor" was the name of Edmund Syl<lb></lb>vester—It was No. 352—the driver of that was John Sylvester, and the conductor John Smith—these two followed us every where we went, and the other omnibuses still pursued the same line of conduct as they had before—when we stopped, the opposition omnibuses stopped also—I saw that done on the 15th—about three weeks after that I began driving—I think No. 348 was the first I drove—I cannot tell which of the opposition omnibuses accompained that—I think it was the "Emperor"—but one of them did, and sometimes both of them—we started from the Wheatsheaf, at Paiddington, and went to the Bank, and the opposition omnibuses accom<lb></lb>pained us, if we stopped they stopped also—If we turned round, they would turn and follow us up the by-streets and any where else—If I met any of the other omnibuses they would stop with me also, so that I had always two with me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Tell us any street into which you turned and they followed you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> we went at nine or ten o'clock, one Sunday evening, to Mr. Savory's, on the other side Camden-town, near the Regent's-park, on pur<lb></lb>pose to see if they would follow us—we stopped there till very nearly two o'clock in the morning—the "Emperor" followed us, and remained there all the time—John Sylvester drove it, and Smith was the conductor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you go to Whitechapel? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I went to Marylechone police-office, which is out of my beat, and the "Emperor" ac<lb></lb>compained me there, and stopped all the time I stopped—I broke down twice, and they stopped at the same time—I once broke dewn in the New-road, and once in the Edgware-road, both out of our road, and they stopped with us, and followed us home—we lengthened one of our omnibuses, No. 349, to Maida-hill—I think on the 6th of July—I drove that at time—the "Emperor" followed me that very day, and pursued the same kind of conduct us before, in running before me—In going to Maida-hill I went through Paddington—If in driving I came within Bolton's times, I had his five omnibuses with me also—he had three minute's time—I think his first time was a quarter before ten o'clock, and he had two three minutes after that—If I came within his first time he would hang back, and take a minute or two of the other man's time, and the other one would hurry to make his time up; so that I had two with me, and very likely three or four—If I came within Bardell's time, they would hang back upon me in the same manner—Richard Bird did the same—Thomas Bird the same—Carpenter, Cowderoy, Hill, Johnson, and Newell did the same—It was he followed me out of my road a day or two after the sale, up Hinde-street, and two or three other streets which I turned up to get out of their way, as they were hunting us so much—Pearce did the same—Parker and Sellick the same—l never saw Robert Trevett drive, but I have seen him on the box of the "Emperor"—I have heard him halloo to them to "Keep at him," and cheering them on—I believe the "Albion" used to put up at night at Trevett's stable, but I did not see it—they used to follow me to</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210206"></xptr>
               <p>the yard at night, and turn round to see if I was coming out again—they would wait for an hour, and very often for two or three hours—when I started in the morning, I have met them at the corner of Southamptom-street, waiting for me, which is within fifty yards of Red-lion-yard, but they generally used to stop at the corner of Edgeware-road—I have gone up Southampton-street, and gone the back way to Paddington, and they have followed me that way—whenever they met me they were sure to follow me—on the 4th of July I went to the White Horse after my father—I saw Cowderoy, Trevett, and Hill there—I believe they had sent for my father over there—I heard Cowderoy say, "That is right, <hi rend="italic">old one,</hi> start half-a-dozen, it will soon bring it to a close; we are such b----y <hi rend="italic">rum ones,</hi> and such <hi rend="italic">out-and-outers"</hi>—and Mr. Hill said, "The <hi rend="italic">old one</hi> is a right one, he ought to be one, he is an old hackney-coach master"—Robert Travett was present at the time, and he had some conversation with him, but I did not exactly hear what it was—they were each of them drinking a great deal, and got pushing each other about in their chairs—Mr. Trevett said, "Why don't you buy a time?"—my father said, "No, I never intend buying a time"—Mr. Trevett said, "It is no good your trying to beat us, for we are such <hi rend="italic">out-and-outers</hi> you can't beat us"—I did not hear any thing said about 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—Richard Bird has abused me very much on the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—he said he wished my b—y <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> was smashed all to pieces—he once said so at the corner of the New-road and once in the City—he said that after the "Zebra," Mr. Johnson's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, had run against the pannel of our <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—I was not with it at the time, but I saw the damage that was done—I dined at Woodgate's, the Royal Oak, pretty nigh every day—I rather think I missed one day—I do not know what street it is in, but it is out of the road—we took our omnibus there, and the other accompanied us—the driver and con<lb></lb>ductor of that omnibus very often dined at the same place that we did—we did—we put up our omnibus at Mr. Davis's—we remained there sometimes half an hour, and sometimes two hours, or more, and the "Emperor" always remained exactly the same time, and started at the same time—It did not go to any yard—It remained outside the door—when we have been going along the road and had not any passengers, we have very often turned off, and sup<lb></lb>posing they had any passengers they would give them away to another <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> and turn round and catch us—I have very often gone a mile or two out of my way to see if they would catch me, and they have always come after me and found me—when I have wanted to take up passengers, they have tried to get them into their own <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—I remeber our calling for Mr. Hillhouse, the surgeon, in Oxford-street, and he requested to be set down at his own door, which is in Holborn—he said that aloud, as he was sitting on the box with me, and the "Emperor" pulled up at his door, and I could not put him down there—If any ladies wanted to come in, they would try to pull before me, so that I should not pull up to the curb-stone to take them up—If a lady had a child in her arms, they would run and take the child out of her arms, and put it into their <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, that I should not get the fare—I have seen Joseph Bardell beckon for his <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> to come up and fol<lb></lb>low me when I have been driving—I have heard John Sylvester say, when he has met Mr. Bolton, "There goes our governor"—Sylvester has said to me, "You had better have bought a time: you have lost a great deal of money now, and a little more would have bought a time"—he has said, "We have times to sell; we want 160<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a piece for them"—he said Mr. Newman had lost 600<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and he wished he had bought a time—I said we should never buy a time—he said it was no use our going on;</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210207"></xptr>
               <p>they should be sure to ruin us—he said they were ordered to follow us wherever we went, and to stop out till ten o'clock at night—(they very often wished me to go to Edgeware, and dared me to go forty or fifty miles into the country, and they would follow)—he has also said it was not use to run in opposition against the Paddington committee, they were so strong—I have not heard Smith say as much as that—he has said, when he has met Mr. Bolton, "That is our governor," or, "Do you see our governor?"—our conductor was Joseph Raines—we stopped on the 26th of July—they had continued to follow us till that day—I think that day they stopped at Paddington—my father came out again on the 29th, and I went out on the 30th with No. 348—the "Emperor" accomopained me then—my omnibus broke down; and when I drove the other <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> the four o'clock journey, they both accompained me—If a passenger tried to get in, they would jump down, and try to persuade him to get into their <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> During the time that this opposition was going on, did you see Cow<lb></lb>deroy drive? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, several times—he drove his own <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, and his con<lb></lb>duct was as much against me as could be to prevent my getting passen<lb></lb>gers—I have seen Newell conducting his own <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, and his conduct to me has been the same as the others, trying to get the passengers into his own <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—when I have come in their time, or before their time, they would hurry on to catch me, and then keep with me—they would run over any other man's time to keep up with me—It was Newell's that followed me out of the road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Richard Bird, Thomas Bird, Cowderoy, or Johnson, ever drive out of their road against you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—they are proprietors, having their own times—when I drove in their times, they ran with me; and they have come out with me, and stopped beyond their own time—I never saw either of them conduct or drive the "Albion" or the "Emperor," but they have cheered them on to go on against me—It was the "Albion" and the "Emperor" which fol<lb></lb>lowed me wherever I went—I have played at skittles once or twice with the men—I have played at skittles at the Royal Oak, with John Sylvester and <hi rend="italic">Brush</hi>, that is Smith—I have played five or ten minutes—I have been there while the game was going on—I will swear I have not played half-a-dozen games—I have dined with Sylvester and Smith, and drank together at dinner—I went to Wales' tea-gardens, at Bayswater—they followed me there, and I think I had one game at skittles—there were seven or eight besides them; that was after business—I went there for pleasure, and to see if they would follow me—we played together, and I think drank together—I do not recollect being at any other places with them—I have drank wine with Mr. Trevett, close to his stable, at Mr. Gamble's—It was some time in June—I went down there, and Mr. Trevett asked me to take a glass of wine with him—he asked me to treat his men—he treated them with some, and I treated them with some.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> That was while all this wickedness was going on? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was at the beginning of it—I did not hear Trevett on that occasion complain that my father had set up an omnibus in opposition, when he knew that the times were filled up—I did not hear any one say so—my father has no partner—he never had one—he never drove an omnibus, but he has one now, which he bought about a fortnight after he began, at the time he was so much annoyed by the other two—I do not know exactly who he bought it of—I believe he had seen Mr. Norton several times before he bought it—I cannot say who he bought it of—he got the money by earning it—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210208"></xptr>
               <p>did not hear my father say who he bought it of—I never saw it before me father had it—I do not know that Mr. Norton had any thing to do with in—I do not know that Mr. Norton ever had any thing to do with omnibuses—I knew a man named Lyons, when we sold him horses—I do not know that he is a friend of Norton's—one of the Lyons did drive for us—I do not know whether my father bought the omnibus of him, or whether Norton found the money—I cannot tell how many omnibuses were on the road between Paddington and the Bank—when my father set up, there were between twenty and thirty; there might be more—there were tune<lb></lb>keepers on the road—I do not know what their business was—when my father's omnibus started, we did not go at any particular time—we went when we could get a load—we tried to start at nine o'clock, but found we could not get a load—I knew there were times at which the different omnibuses ran, but I did not know at what time they went.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I understand your father's omni<lb></lb>buses started on the 8th of June, and there was no opposition till the 15th? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes there was; but the "Emperor" and the "Albion" did not start till then—Newell's omnibus followed us out of the line of road—I do not know that my father's omnibus, on the first day it started, went out of the line to Market-street, near Trevett's stable, and waited till his omnibus came out, and stuck to it all day—I did not accompany my father's omni<lb></lb>bus all the way that day—I do not know that, one thursday, one of my father's omnibuses went out of the way to Bolton's stable, and waited for his omnibus, and hunted that all day—I never heard it from my father—such a thing could not have happened on the regular road without my seeing it—I could not help driving close to some of the other omnibuses—I did not drive my pole through Mr. Gaywood's omnibus—they threw their door open, and caught my wheel, and broke their door—I did not know that there were quite enough omnibuses on that road, before my father startede his—we have not put passengers out of our omnibus, to turn and hunt these other omnibuses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say that Newell's omnibus followed you, was he driving on that occasion? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you been in your father's employ as a horse-dealer? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I have been with him ever since I was born—I do not know that before we started, there was an omnibus went every three minutes—we live opposite Day and Martin's—some omnibuses stop there, but I do not know that I they all do—I cannot say whether there is one stops every three minutes—I went backwards and forwards with my father's omnibus—the first week I watched them, my father merely gave me instructions to keep them steady—I do not know the omnibus, No. 245—I do not know George Hoby and Robert Weston, the driver and conductor of it by name—I may know them by sight—I drove my father's omnibus latterly—I might have driven half a journey about a fortnight after they started—I never saw my father's omnibus follow No. 245, or any other omnibus, but I have seen others follow my father's—when our omnibus drove against Gaywood's, they were not running against us, as they were standing at the bottom of Holborn-hill, and they threw the door open before I had time to pull up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1179" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1179" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1179" type="surname" value="MANSELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1179" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD MANSELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I went into the service of Mr. Bray on the 8th of July—I was then conductor to his L'addubgton omnibus, No. 348—I have driven both Nos. 348 and 349—I am still in his service—I drive No. 349 now—the "Albion" used to follow and accompany No. 348 wherever it</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210209"></xptr>
               <p>went—I know Bolton, the two Bardells, richard Bird, thomas bird, Caroeb<lb></lb>ter, cowderoy, Hill, Johnson, Newell, Pearce, Parkes, Sellick, and Trevett's omnibuses—they all have obstructed and opposed me—they have drawn before me, and put their poles close to my door—sometimes I have been in one time, and sometimes in another, and whichever time I have been in they hyave gone before me—when a passenger was coming they would put their pole up to my door, so that a passenger could not get in—John Hit<lb></lb>chings, (that is Gough,) and Thomas Trevett have abusede my inside pas<lb></lb>singers—at the corner of Regent-street—they have driven their pole close enough to alarm any female who was getting in—they have stopped be<lb></lb>fore me, so as to obstruct my going on—If there were two carts, they would stop between them to prevent my passing—that has frequently been the case—I remember Mr. Bray's omnibuses being given up for a time—It was on the 27th of July—I saw Gough get off his box, and I saw Trevett go into a shop—I then saw blue ribbons on the "emperor" and "Albion"—both Gough and Trevett were with the "Albion"—I cannot say who was with the "Emperor," but I saw them driving one after the other—I have seen the "Emperoro" put up at night at Mr. Bolton's yard, in North-wharf road—I do not know whether he lived there—one night, after my <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> had gone home, I rode home with Trevett and Gough in the "Albion," to Trevett's yard, and we had a glass of something to drink—that might be ten days or a fortnight before the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> was stopped—when I have been driving, Trevett has interfered with my passengers, and told them I was go<lb></lb>ing to Charing-cross, by which means I have had several passengers refuse going with me—I saw persons in the omnibus when they had the blue ribbon, but I cannot say who they were—I still continue with Mr. Bray's bus, and the "Emperor" still continues to follow me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you on the road before Mr. Bray started? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was on the Elephant and Castle road—I know ther were no opposition buses on the Paddington road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You drank together? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They came to the same house, but at last we quarrelled; we then went to another house, and they followed us there—we dined in the parlour by ourselves, and then they went back to the house where they had been be<lb></lb>fore; we went to Mr. Friend's, a gin-shop—when I first went I have played a game at skittles with them, and we dined together.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1180" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1180" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1180" type="surname" value="RAYNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1180" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES RAYNER</persName>
                  </hi>. I was conductor to one of Mr. Bray's blue <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>—I began on the 8th of June—we were obstructed by the other omnibuses on the road—the "Emperor" and "Albion" were put on about a week after we began—I became conductor to No. 349, which went on to Maida-hill, and the other omnibuses continued the same mode of obstruction—the "Em<lb></lb>peror" followed me when I went out of the way—on one ocoasion it fol<lb></lb>lowed me up to Mr. Savory's, at Portman-town—It waited till near two in the morning—the "Emperor" followed me out of the road on several oc<lb></lb>casions; if we turned round, they turned round with us—about six weeks after I started, the "Emperor" broke the door-pannel of our omnibus with his pole—he came after us rather too sharp, and the pole ran up against our door, and broke the pannel—I saw the blue ribbons on their horses' heads in the Edgeware-road—I rode on the steps of the "Emperor" to Thomas Bird's yard, on the 27th, between eleven and twelve o'clock in the morning—I saw Mr. Hill in the omnibus—I did not notice any body else—he went and asked if Mr. Bird was at home—I do not know what answer he received—I left them at the yard.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210212"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do not you recollect re<lb></lb>ceiving orders from Mr. Bray to go against Trevett? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not re<lb></lb>collect it—he said he did not understand the business; he left it entirely to his men to go in what times they liked—I received a direction to go in whose time I thought proper—I do not recollect receiving positive direc<lb></lb>tions from Mr. Bray to go against Trevett—I was conductor to the om<lb></lb>nibus driven by Lee—I do not recollect going with Mann—there has been two Mann's at work—we did not receive directions from Mr. Bray to go against Trevett in particular—he said Trevett's time was a very good time, and so was Mr. Bird's, and wer could not do better than go in them—Lee was present when Mr. Bray gave those directions—I did not tell Teevett I had orders to go in his time, nor I did not hear Lee tell him so—I first went with the omnibus on a Monday—the regular line is from the Wheatsheaf to Bank.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> On that day did you go down Market-street, to the place where Mr. Trevett's omnibuses put up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know whether it was the first day—I certainly went to a public-house there, to dine, close by where Trevett puts up—that is out of the line of road—I remember going there several times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you remember when you went triumphantly down Market-street, saying, "We will soon <hi rend="italic">dish up</hi> the old <hi rend="italic">Snob,</hi> we will soon melt his wax for him?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not say much a thing, nor hear such a thing—there was no one in my omnibus—I have not boasted that I would melt the cobler's wax.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you orders from Mr. Bray to go down Market-street? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, Sir; we went where we pleased to drive, and they followed us.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> But you followed them when you went to their house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was Mr. Gamble's house we went to—I know Trevett's men go to that house occasionally—I dined with two or three of them there that day—It is a house where coachmen and omnibus-men generally go.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean to swear that they go out of their line of road? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We were not plying for passengers—we went to have our dinner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the observations about the time when you first began, or afterwards? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Afterwards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you know Mr. Bray before you were en<lb></lb>gaged by him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had never seen him—I was recommended to him by Mr. Davidson, and am in his employment still—I have been in the ring—there is not a warrant against me now for manslaughter, for killing a man in a boxing match—I do not deny that I was severn years ago at Hammersmith—I remember <hi rend="italic">Paddy</hi> Flynn and another being transported—I have fought two or three battles.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have said the pole of the "Emperor" was driven into your pannel <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; that was in conse<lb></lb>quence of my pulling up suddenly, to prevent running over somebody, I believe.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Now with respect to this public-house near Trevett's stable, did you not wait there, colse to Trevett's yard, till his omnibus came out, and then go with them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We went with them to town and back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The question was, did you wait? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We did not parti<lb></lb>cularly wait for them—we went with them when they went.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not follow one of Trevett's? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not recollect seeing one of them—we came away at the same time.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210213"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I think Lee, Mann, and Beals were servants of Mr. Bray as well as yourself? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you not told Mr. Bird, when you were running your omni<lb></lb>buses against his, that you should not have done it but you had received orders? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I certainly received orders to go in his time, as well as Mr. Trevett's, as it was a very good time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Now I give you notice that Lee and Beals are here; upon your solemn oath, have you not said that to Mr. Bird? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, Sir; I have not said any thing to him in particular—I have not told him I was sorry to oppose him—I never had any any conversation with either of the Mr. Birds about going in their times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you orders to go in Mr. Bird's time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not assign that as a reason to Mr. Bird? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; Birds name was mentioined to me, and Trevett's and Johnson's was also mentioned by Mr. Bray.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Then if Bray has sworn that he never directed any servant of his to run in opposition, or in the time of any body by name, has he not sworn what is wickedly false? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know what Mr. Bray has sworn—I worked for Mr. Bray before he bought the third omnibus—I do not know who he bouoght it of—I have not known Mr. Norton till within the last month—I have seen him about Mr. Bray's premises since that time—I have never been in any trouble myself—I have not for a long period get my living by fighting—I have fought pitched battles for money—I know Lyons, he used to be an omnibus proprietor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined. Q.</hi> You never saw Mr. Norton till the last month? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—the directions I first received from Mr. Bray, were to go in what time I liked; as he did not know what time, he would leave it all to his men—about the first or second weeek after I went, he said that Bird's and Trevett's were very good times, we could not do better than to go in their times—their time was about nint o'clock in the morning, or a little after—It is just upon seven years since I fought my last pitched battle—I never killed a man in my life—I was present at a fight where a man was kille, and two men were transported for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1181" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1181" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1181" type="surname" value="SWAITZER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1181" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY SWAITZER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk in the Stamp Office. On the 15th of June, Thomas Bolton, in the name of John Bolton, obtained a supple<lb></lb>ment license, in the name of Edmund Sylvester; and at the same time, Robert Trevett obtained a supplemental license, adding the name of Thomas Corbett to his own—the first was for the "Emperor," and the second for the "Albion;" and on the 6th of July, Bray obtained a sup<lb></lb>plemental license, to go to Maida Hill—and on the same day, Bolton and Sylvester obtained a supplemental license, lengthening the distance for the "Emperor" to Maida Hill.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1182" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1182" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1182" type="surname" value="NASH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1182" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM NASH</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 27th of July, I saw an omnibus and the horses had blue ribbons—I cannot tell the number of the omnibus, nor who drove it—I did not see either of the defendants there, to the best of my knowledge—I know Mr. Cowderoy—I do not recollect that I have drank with him—I saw him at the Feathers that day, I believe—I do not recollect seeing him in the box of the omnibus when the horses had blue ribbons—I cannot recollect who I saw—I am in the habit of standing at my gate, and seeing them go past.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1183" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1183" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1183" type="surname" value="TURNBULL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1183" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH TURNBULL</persName>
                  </hi>. I was the proprietor of an omnibus, which ran from Paddington to the Bank, but I have not been so for nine months past, There was a committee of the Paddington omnibus proprietors, they called them</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210214"></xptr>
               <p>selves a commitee—I belonged to it before I ceased to be proprietor—I was a member of the committee—I certainly went at times, but very seldom—I went three or four times—I believe it generally consisted of the whole of the propietors of the omnibuses running from paddington to the Bank over the stones—they met at the New Inn—I have been there, and at the Lion in the Edgeware-road—I have at times received notices to go—I can<lb></lb>not recollect whether they were printed or written—the times of meeting were very distant indeed—I seldom or ever went—I was a proprietor from the commencement of the running on the stones, which was in 1832—I know Mr. Bolton—I have seen him at the committee, and James and Joseph Bardell, Richard Bird, Thomas Bird, Carpentor, Cowderoy, Hill, Johnson, Newell, pearce, parkes, Selick, and Robert Trevett—It only consisted of proprietors—the last time I was at the committee there was a demand made upon me for 60<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 70l—I ceased to be a proprietor nine months ago—I disposed of it altogether to my son, but I have not settled with him—we drew no agreement at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Does not that consist of your good-will obtained from running your omnibuses at certain hours from Pad<lb></lb>dington down to the Bamk? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Certainly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined. Q.</hi> There were certain times allotted to you to run; what times werethey, three minutes? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I had six times allocated to me in the day—the other parties were not allowed to run at the same minutes—If any strangers have interfered, I was to do the best I could with them—I believe strangers have interfered, I do not recollect—there were arrangements made by the committee if a stranger interfered, but I can hardly tell what, as I so seldom attended—I do not recollect being there when any stranger had interfered—It is some time since I was there—I cannot tell whether, when I was there last, anything was stated by the committee of any arrange<lb></lb>ment having been made before, of what was to be done when any stranger interfered—there was none that I recollect.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1184" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1184" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1184" type="surname" value="BALL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1184" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN BALL</persName>
                  </hi> I am a perfumer, and live in Oxford-street. I have observed Mr. Bray's omnibuses, and the conduct of the other omnibuses towards them—I know the "Emperor" and the "Albion"—we have been very much annoyed by these omnibuses running one against another—about six weeks back I wanted to get into Bray's omnibus, and the "Em<lb></lb>peror" came right against the steps, so as to prevent my getting in—I have seen such conduct on several occasions—the "Emperor" and the "Al<lb></lb>bion" appeared to obstruct Mr. Bray's omnibuses by running—when any person wanted to get into Mr. Bray's, the "Emperor" would run across the steps, sometimes their pole came almost on the pavement.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Has Mr. Bray's gone at a quick pace along the street? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, Sir; I have seen it go at a quick pace—I have seen it run to get out of the way of the others—I have not seen it racing parallel with them, because they have gone before him or behind his—he has gone about six miles an hour—I will not swear he has not gone eight—I never knew of their doing anything improper—I should not be surprised if they had been summoned for furious driving; that is what oc<lb></lb>curs every day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean that the "Emperor" and the "Albion" drew up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It was the "Emperor" that drew up—the "Albion" impedes by getting before the omnibus—I have seen them both with it—I have generally seen the "Emperor" be<lb></lb>hind, and the "Albion" before—I think so—I think there are several om<lb></lb>nibuses called by those names.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210215"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have observed these omnibuses, and the "Em<lb></lb>peror" and "Albion" constantly; upon your oath, can you state that the "Em<lb></lb>peror" and "Albion" have been impeding Bray's, or did Bray's annoy them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have seen the "Emperor" oppose Bray's omnibus—that is what I swear to—I could not swear to the driver of the "Emperor"—I put down the number—It is 352.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did you make any communication to Mr. Norton? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know him—I was supcenaed to attend to give evi<lb></lb>dence—I never gave evidence but in this Court—I have talked of it to my neighbours—I saw Bray last night—I never saw him before—I did not speak to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What is the number of the "Albion?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> 177—I marked it on the back of my subpœna.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1185" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1185" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1185" type="surname" value="TEMPLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1185" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD TEMPLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a brazier and oilman, and live in Prince's-street, Cavendish-square. I know Mr. Bray's omnibus—I have seen it when one of Bolton's omnibuses has been before it, and one of Bardell's along with it—I spoke to young Bray—he nodded to me—he then turned round and went back again, up Oxford-street, and Bolton's followed him—I told the coachman, who happened to be young Mr. Bray, that what I had seen I should be most happy to say in any Court afterwards—I have seen Bolton's following Mr. Bray's about—I saw it last Saturday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1186" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1186" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1186" type="surname" value="RAWLINGS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1186" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN RAWLINGS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a linen-draper, and live at No. 133, Oxford-street. I have noticed Bray's omnibus, in their way from Paddington, along Oxford-street, for some months—I have seen it almost daily—I have noticed the conduct of other omnibuses towards it, the "Emperor" for one—they were chasing Mr. Bray's; one was before and one behind—I cannot recollect what was the name of the other omnibus—the one before ob<lb></lb>structed him in his buisness, and the one behind interfered with the pass<lb></lb>engers who wanted to get in—I have seen that frequently—they pulled the people away frequently—their pole was nearly close to the door, so as to prevent any person getting in—I cannot say that I have noticed any other omnibus interfere in this way but the "Emperor" and one more—Bray's omnibus was obstructed in its free course by them—I do not recollect that I have seen Bray's act improperly to them, but I have seen the opposition strong against Bray.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Bray's ever act so as to oppose them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I never noticed that.</p>
