               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RATCLIFF</hi>. I am a carver, gilder, and picture dealer, and live in Holborn. I know Mr. Bray's omnibus, and have occasionally ridden in it—I have noticed the conduct of Mr. Bray's omnibus, and the conduct of other omnibuses with respect to him, so much so that I have been compelled to apply to the police—about two months ago I was at Maida Hill, and wished to get into Bray's omnibus, another drew up, and had I not have been as quick as possible, I think the pole would have come against my head—I did not take notice of that omnibus—It appeard to me to be done to prevent my getting into Bray's omnibus—when I have passed through Holborn, I have seen one or more omnibus accompanying Bray's; but I did not notice them, as I never expected it to go beyond self-protection about which I went to Bow-street—on the occasion I am now speaking of, the other omnibuses were coming from Maida to the City—I remember one with the name "Emperor" on it, but I have since seen there are one</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210217"></xptr>
               <p>or two other of the name—one of the others was No. 244, the other was 266—I believe one was Mr. Hill's, and the other was Mr. Bardell's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where did you get the number? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I took it in the first instance, and I went last night to Bow-street, to get the two numbers, as they were summoned there by me on the 11th of August—one was Hill's and the other Bardell's—I wish to say, that the driver of Mr. Hill's was most insolent—his language was most dreadful—Sir Frederick Roe said he would fine him, 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. the next time—the driver of Mr. Bardell's had more sense, and behaved with more propriety—I never saw any thing improper in the conduct of Mr. Bray's omnibus—I live at No. 213, Holborn, nearly faeing Day and Martin's, twenty-five or thirty-five doors from Mr. Bray's—he lives up a yard—I have known him some years, and when I rido in an omnibus, it is generally by him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KNOWLES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> In connexion with what was it you mentioned the name of Bardell? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The two omnibuses had blocked up the way of Bray's, to prevent my getting in, and the police summoned them—I went to prove the case—I cannot tell which of the Bardells it was—there was the name of Bardell on one of the omnibuses—they stood and blocked up the whole road—I dare say there were thirty or forty carriages which could not go on—I begged of the first man to go on, and he refused—Bardell's, I think, was the last.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Then in point of fact, he could not have got forward? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He could have given way to give space, but not quite suffcient for the others to go past—he could no get out, but still he might have accommodsted a little if he liked—he could not get back, there were twenty or thirty carriages behind him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1192" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1192" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1192" type="surname" value="HUDSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1192" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HUDSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tobacconist, and have lived in Oxford-street upwards of thirty years. I know Mr. Bray's omnibus—I have observed it interrupted by other omnibuses for the past two or three months—I have seen the "Emperor," No. 352, and the other, No. 177, with "Thomas Corbett" on it, one before and one behind Bray's, and they driven up against his steps to prevent the passengers going by him, and half a dozen others have done the same—there must have been a great deal of danger in peo<lb></lb>ple getting in or out of his omnibus—I have seen Bray's turn, and the others have turned about also—I have complained to the ploice repeatedly—I have complained to Martin, the officer—the other omnibuses have driven so fast that unless I had stopped them, I could not complain to their con<lb></lb>ductors about it—I have on one or two occasions stopped them, and said if they drove so fast I should take their numbers, and go to to the police<lb></lb>office.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Upon those former occasions, have you seen Bray turning round, following the others, and using the same course that they did to him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you call on Mr. Bolton, and propose that they should pay 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a-piece, and settle the matter? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I never called on him—I wrote him a letter, he them called on me—I did not propose that they should pay 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a-piece, and settle the matter—the letter I wrote was complaining of the insolence and abusive conduct of his drivers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> But I am talking about what you said to him; upon your oath, did you not propose to him that a sum of money should be paid, and the busi<lb></lb>ness should be settled? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I did not proposem an arrangement—he proposed an arrangement; he said, he should not like to come to the bar of the Old Bailey—I said, "I think you are right, Sir, not to have it said after<lb></lb>wards</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210218"></xptr>
               <p>that you had been at the bar of the Old Bailey"—he asked what I thought Mr. Bray expected—I said he was a perfect stranger to me—I had come forward to support Mr. Bray, together with the whole of my neigh<lb></lb>bours, to put down this racing against people as they had done; and that Mr. Bray had told me he had lost, by being opposed by Mr. Bolton and others, between 300<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and 400<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I stated to him first of all, that it was a most abominable thing, that the self-elected committee of Paddington pro<lb></lb>prietors should say the whole of the King's highway belonged to them, and that no person should come there unless they paidd 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—he said, "I should not have run an omnibus against him had not his man come to my yard, and insulted my people, and I put on the omnibus to run hid off the road—now do you want any thing more?"</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many times has your conduct been questioned in courts of justice, for gross usury, extortion, and fraud? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Now I mean to say, upon my oath, that sucj things may have been said and counsel will take liberty to say such things, and most untruly sometimes, but nothing of that kind ever occurred—I never was before a Magistrate on any charge, not even a watch-house charge—I have never been questioned in any case in courts of justice.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you discount bills? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No I—do not make loans to people, and then supply them with snuff-boxes—only in a way of business, like other tradesmen—I never was a money-lender in my life—my name is Hudson, of Oxford-street, a tobacconist—I take the liberty of saying that I am notorious for not being a money-lender.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1193" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1193" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1193" type="surname" value="COLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1193" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a chemist and druggist, and live at No. 101, High Holborn. I know Bray's omnibuses—I have observed other omnibuses near them when they beem going along the road—I suppose a thousand times—the others were driving continually before and behind them, and trying to prevent passengers, alarming ladies, and driving so close behind it as to make it dangerous for females to get in—I have never seen Bray's do so to the other omnibuses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1194" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1194" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1194" type="surname" value="PRIESTLY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1194" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD PRIESTLY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in High Holborn, and am a bookseller. I have seen Mr. Bray's omnibuses, and other omnibuses with them, one behind and one before, quite close—I have seen that frequently—I do not know the names of the other omnibus—one was the "Emperor. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did it appear, from what you saw of the two omnibuses, one before and one behind, that there was fair competition or unfair? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Unfair; I think that means were made use of to prevene Mr. Bray carrying on his business fairly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1195" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1195" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1195" type="surname" value="BLOOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1195" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT BLOOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am proprietor of an omnibus. I remember on the 27th of July, seeing the "Emperor" with blue ribons to the horses, by the toll-gate—there were several persons with it, one or two, I can recollect—I saw Mr. Bolton at the gate taking money, and the eldest Mr. Trevett was at the garden gate about five minutes before—I saw Hill—I do bot recollect seeing Cowderoy—there was an observation made by Gough, who was driving the "Albion," the oppostion <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> that went against Mr. Brau's—he was driving young Trevett—he amde an observation loud enough for people to h ear, I should think—he said, "We shall be with you to<lb></lb>morrow"—I made an appeal to the gentlemen with em and said, "So long as you continue with me I don's care for the committee"—I have hasd op<lb></lb>postion against me, but not by Trevett.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who was it? Cowderoy's omnibus was driven against me one day,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210219"></xptr>
               <p>about a month after—there was no omnibus put against me on the morrow, as Gough said.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say Boton was at the gate, taking money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I am told he is collector of the tolls there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1196" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1196" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1196" type="surname" value="COLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1196" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am landlord of Mr. Corbett, in Lamb's-buildings, Bar<lb></lb>bican—he pays 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year—he is not in arrears—I believe he is in the shoe line.</p>
               <p>A verdict of <rs id="t18350921-2116-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350921-2116-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350921-2116-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>acquittal</rs> was here taken for James Bardell and Joseph Bardell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. PRENDERGAST, PHILLIPS, CLARKSON, KNOWLES</hi>, <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">BODKIN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">addressed the Court and Jury in behalf of the defendants, and called the following witnesses.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1197" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1197" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1197" type="surname" value="TREVETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1197" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN TREVETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am son of the defendant, Robert Trevett. He has some omnibuses which run from Paddington to the Bank—I remember Mr. Bray starting two omnibuses—I do not remember the day of the month, but I saw them at the Wheatsheaf on Whit-Monday—John Lee was the driver of one of them, and I believe h is conductor was <hi rend="italic">Jem</hi> Raines—the driver of the other was Henry Mann, better known by the name of <hi rend="italic">Cuddy</hi> Mann, and James Trevett, who is a cousin of mine, was the conductor—he had once been in my father's employment some time ago—Lee had been in my father's service, but had left, and Mann had been employed to do odde work when other men were away, or ill—the first I saw of Brau's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> was at the Wheatsheaf, and when one of my father's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> started from the Wheatsheaf, one of Bray's started with it—I think Lee drove that—my father's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> started at its regular time—my father has has omnibuses on that road about five years, I should think—when Shillibeer started in Sep<lb></lb>tember, he started the first omnibus about January—on the day Bray's omnibuses appeared, my father's omnibus went down to the Bank, I sup<lb></lb>pose—Robert Willis drove it—I cannot recollect who was the conductor—I did not see Bray in the course of that day—I saw my father's omnibus, shout five o'clock that day, come down to the stable, in Market-street, Paddington, and Bray's omnibus followed my father's down to the stable, and passed by—that was out of the regular line of road—my father's omni<lb></lb>bus stood outside the horses went into the stable, and staid there about forty minutes—It was tea-time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did the conductor or driver of Bray's omnibus say any thing while they were following your father's to the stable? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; as they passed they said, "We will break the b----y cobler; we will melt his b----y wax"—that was either the driver or the conductor—I believe it wa <hi rend="italic">Cuddy</hi> Mann—my father is a bot and shoemaker, and lives in Finasbury—I re<lb></lb>member my father's omnibus starting again that eventing—while we had been waiting, Bray's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> were at the Fountain Abbey, the public-house at the corner—our <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> always go roung that corner, and as soon as our buses turned that corner, I saw Bray's men get up in haste and follow them our—two <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> went from the yard together, and both Bray's followed them—they started from the Wheatsheaf, at Paddington, which is about half a mile from the Fountain Abbey.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you ever observed your omnibuses and Bray's on the line of road? <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Yes; I think on Whit-Tuesday, the 9th of June, I saw Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> and my father's in Regent-circus, Oxfort-street—that is the place they generally call at—the Magistrates will not let them stand there, so they trail gently bu; but they were thenstanding at the corner of Ox<lb></lb>ford-street—I saw a gentleman passenger in the act of getting into my father's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, and Lee, who was then conductor to Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, went to my</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210220"></xptr>
               <p>father's <hi rend="italic">bus,</hi> and pulled the passenger away, and put him into Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—he put his hands round the gentleman, and pulled him right away—I was not near enough to hear any thing said—Lee and the conductor of my father's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> got fighting through it—the fight did not last above a mi<lb></lb>nute—some one parted them—the omnibises then went off together—I believe ours was a little first—they were very nearly abreast—the "Al<lb></lb>bion, "No. 177, was my father's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—he has no partner in any way—I have seen Bray's and my father's racing together since the time I spoke of, but not to notice any particular circumstance.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know there is a Paddington committee? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not—there is what is erronecously called a committee, a meeting of the proprie<lb></lb>tors of that road—they meet on Thursday nights at the White Lion—I have been at the meeting—It is held in the first floor front room—any one may walk in—there has been no secrecy when I was present—there is very seldom any thing done there at all—sometimes some of the pre<lb></lb>prietors would come and tell another that his men had been kincking up a disturbance on the road—It was always settled between the person who made the complaint, and the person whose servants were complained of—I have known of drivers being discharged by the proprietors on account of—their misconduct—I cannot say who it was—the subscription that was paid was half-a-crown a week for each member—It was to pay the time-keepers—there is no other subscription among the proprietors that I know of—the half-crown was not paid there in general—one of the conductors pays for his three omnibuses down Oxford-street—there are several time-keepers—one is deputed to receive the subscriptions, and pay the others—I never knew of any subscrition between my father and the other pro<lb></lb>prietors, to support any opposition while Mr. Bray was running his omni<lb></lb>buses—I have the sole management of my father's omnibus business, and had it at that time—If there had been any subscription made to oppose Bray, it must have come under my knowledge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BUMPUS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> This which is "er<lb></lb>roneously called a committee" meets at the White Lion? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I do not know that I have ever omitted going for the last four months—some<lb></lb>times there are only two or three of the proprietors there—It is called the Paddington Committee—I do not know of any jurisdiction that it has—the proprietors who formerly fixed the times go to that meeting—they all go occasionally there—I never knew of any secretary—my father has had an omnibus, called the "Tally Ho," on that road for some time—that was put on against a man's omnibus of the name of Lewis, and run him down last autumn—I know the name of George Craig—I never knew he was a pro<lb></lb>prietor—I know Shillibeer personally—I do not remember his being run against—not for six months, I do not—I remember an omnibius with the name of Newman on it; that was run against, and run off, and he sold it to Bolton, I believe—Bolton set up an opposition against him, I believe.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did not Bolton's always follow Newman's wherever it went? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have seen it before it, and behind, and on the same line of road—It was one of Bolton's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>—I do not remember the name of it, or who was the driver on conductor—Mrs. Turnbull was a proprictor up to the last nine months—I never remember seeing her name on a <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>. nor her attending the commit<lb></lb>tee—I did nto attend them rugularly till the last Christmas—I have bees there before—I do not remember seeing her there—I do not remember her having an omnibus run against her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I ask you whether the very same omnibus that ran against Newman was not put on against Mrs. Turnbull? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never, to my knowledge—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210221"></xptr>
               <p>never was present where Mrs. Turnbull was, nor when any thing was said about a demand of 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. upon her, or any other sum.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What is the expense of running an omnibus from Paddington if you get no customers? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About 14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a-week; it depends on the number of journeys it runs, and whether a man is fortunate in his cattle; that is for one <hi rend="italic">bus,</hi> five journeys a-day—I do not know how many proprietors there are—I never reckoned them up—I know Thomas Evans and George Bingham.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> As far as I understand, your being at Regent-street was a mere ac<lb></lb>cident? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was there for the purpose of watching—I think it was after dinner—I thought I woulde take a walk down the the road, to see in what manner Bray worked his <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> against my father.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say that you believe the number of your father's omnibus was 177: just recollect, was not the No. 177 upon the "Albion" that was put against Bray on the 15th? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I will not swear to that being the number on that day—theree is more than one bus of my father's on the road—when a new license is taken, there is not always a new number—Thomas Corbett is a boot-clicker—he is foreman to my father in his shop—I remember the time when it was thoought that Bray was off the road, when his horses went for sale—I do not know that the "Albion" had the horses arrayed in blue ribbons—I supped that night with the people at the White Lion—my fa<lb></lb>ther was present—I did not see Bolton there, nor Cowderoy—he might have been there without my seeing him—there were a great number of persons—the room was full—they were the coachmen and the conductors of any om<lb></lb>nibuses, I believe—I do not know who paid—I never saw my father pay any thing—I do not believe he did pay any thing—I do not think he could pay without my knowing it—I sat close to him—I did not pay any thing,</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Tell me somebody that was there beside your father—was Gough there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I think he was—I did not see Sullivan there—I do not know Smith—I did not see either of the Bardells, nor Carpenter, nor either of the Birds—I do not know that Johnson was there, nor Hill, nor Pearce—he might be there—Thomas Evans was there, to the best of my knowledge—the room was full of a number of people.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Am I to understand that you do not recollect any person but Gough, your father, and Evans? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I will not swear to any other person being there—I was there, I should think, an hour and a half—I had a glass of gin and water after supper—there was nobody in the chair that I know of, or at the head of the room; it was all confusion, sometimes one sat at my right hand, and sometimes another—my father sat next to me on my left hand, part of the time—I cannot tell who sat at my other hand any part of the time—I do not know who paid—I understood that Evans and Cowderou's omnibuses had had a quarrel, and had been racing together for a few days, and had settled their difference, and they had a supper over it—I did not see blue ribbons on the horses in the "Albion. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not individually give a sum of money towards that supper in the morning? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I did not see my fathe give any thing—he goes down in the City in the morning, and from time to time he goes with the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—I cannot tell whether Cowderoy does—I have seen him on <hi rend="italic">buses,</hi> driving—my father's first time in the morning, is about twenty minutes after nine o'clock, and he has three times—his next journey is about twelve o'clock, or a few minutesw after, and his next time about a quarter before three o'clock—the "Albion," which runs against Bray, came to my father's yard every night.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210222"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Does he continue from that time up to this to have the same three times? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He has three omnibuses running down Oxford-street—one does not run with the other two the whole day, two follow cach other every time—the first of all that he has starts before twenty minutes after Bine o'clock, about a quarter of an hour or twenty minntes before it—I do not know the precise time that the <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> start, I trust that to the men—the second <hi rend="italic">bus;</hi> is about twenty minntes after nine o'clock, and the third twenty—three minutes after—we have the same times now for two of them, but one was shifted about a fornight ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What I want to know is this., whether you have continued these three first omnibuses at these times, up to within a fortnight? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; we have—my father has always run an omnibus at those times—It has not always run in his name—one has been running latterly with Corbett's name on it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Whenever Bray set out, at whatever time, nice, ten, or eleven o'clock, did not that omnibus with Corbett's name on it set out, whenever Bray's. out? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> And did it not confine itself to those times? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At first it did—our "Albion" time changed after Bray's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Your omnibus always went with one of his? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Bray's went with one or other of our omnibuses—both Bray's went with one of ours from Whit—Monday to about Wednesday, with the exception of one journey—after that there was only one of Brav's with ours—the first day his started with the second omnibus we had that morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you say that Bray ran with one of your omnibuses, when<lb></lb>ever it went, was not that the one that had Corbett's name on it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; Corbett's name was put on about a week after Whit—Monday—Bray's con<lb></lb>tinued to run against one of my father's which had not Corbett's name on—I have seen it at different times of the day—one day at one time—some times at another—sometimes he stopped at the same time we did, and some<lb></lb>time he went on, just as it suited his own fancy—he did that from the very beginning—those which I term the regular <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> kept on at the regular time—the others stopped with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever send your horses down to H olborn, to change the horses in that one that ran against Bray's? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, occasionally; only to that one, that was the "Albion, "No. 117, I believe, but we have two or three "Albions"—I do not know that that "Albion" ever stopped for Bray's omnibus, when it was in Bray's yard—I have not the slightest no<lb></lb>tion that our omnibus ever stopped in Holbom or Southampton-street, while Bray's was in the yary—It was sent to Holborn, because Bray's men said they would not give them time to change, they would make that pair of horses work all day long, when Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> was working against our regu<lb></lb>lar one—If they saw the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> he but on to protect our regular once, they would turn down some of the back streets, and if we stopped he would pop out of some of the streets.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did they do? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They turned down the streets to lose the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> we put on to protect our regular ones, and would wait, and watch till they saw our regular <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> coming, and then go on in front of them, to pick up the passengers which they would have, and we had nothing to protect ourselves with, if this other <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> had not kept with them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How soon after Mr. Bray put on his omnibus did your father put on an extra one? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> My father did not, I put it on—It on—Bray's ran against our <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> when they came down by our stables—I saw they were waiting there—I sent this extra <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> out, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210223"></xptr>
               <p>gave the coachman directions, "if Bray's omnibus runs against ours, you run against his—If he don't interfere with us, you come home again, and don't interfere with him"—that was on the Monday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Supposing Bray had not opposed any of your omnibuses in the way you have stated, should you have put on an extra omnibus? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; if he had not run agiust our omnibuses, we should not have put the extra one on against his.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean if he had not put it on at all, or run in the manner he did? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> If he had not run in the manner he did againat us—If he bad run against other proprietors, it was other people's business.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Before you put on that extra omnibus, had you or your father, to your knowledge, consulted with any other proprietors about putting it on? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, we had not—In fact, my father never gave me orders to put it on, I put it on my own account.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean this "Albion, 177?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I took it off the New-road to do it—my father has three omnibuses on the New-road, and I took that off, to the stones—the New-road omni<lb></lb>bus had been paying its way, and this was a losing concern, but I took it off to proteet the others—I took that one because there was no other omni<lb></lb>bus in the yard fit to go to work.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you put on another in the New-road? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, most certainly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did you start this? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On the Monday—Bray had been three joureys against our regular omnibuses that day—I then sent this extra one out—he went down with our buses the fourth joumey—both of his continued for about three days to run at our regular hours—then one of Bray's left us—the other still continued at the regular hours—his <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> sometimes stopped where ours did—I gave the men orders, if he did not go with ours, not to go with him; but he continued in our time for about a fortnight—some of the men told me that he atarted from one startiong-point in the road, and would go a little way, turn a street, and come out in front of another; and they asked me what they were to do—they told me Bray's men dared them to come with them—I said, "Well, if they dare you to go with them, go with them wherever they go. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1198" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1198" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1198" type="surname" value="WILLIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1198" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT WILLIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a driver in Me. Trevett's employ. I drove the "Old Albion," No. 174—the first time it went was at twenty-one minutes past nine o'clock; the next was three minutes past twelve o'clock; and the next, twelve minutes before three o'clock—I remember White-Monday—I went off that morning, at my usual time, from the Wheatsheaf, at Pad<lb></lb>dington—there was another omnibus of ours that went down the yard with me, or nearly so—Mr. Trvett's omnibus, the "Triumph," was a there—when I got to the Wheatsheaf, I saw, in two or three minutes, two omnibuses, with the name of "Aaron Bray" on the side—I had about nine minutes to stop—they came up, and saud, "Now for the old <hi rend="italic">cobbler;</hi> we will give him a turn"—this was at the Wheatsheaf door—when I started at my time, one of Bray's omnibuses atarted with me; and where I atoppes, they stopped—I first stopped at the corner of the New-road, at the Crown—Bray was before me at that time—our omnibus always stops there—Bray stopped there till I started, and then he stopped too—I went next to the New Inn, and stopped there; and Bray stopped too—he was generally before me—when I stopped, or went on, he stopped or went on too—If passengers came to my omnibus, and I stopped, he would pull up</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210224"></xptr>
               <p>and wait to see whether I went on—we pulled up for a passenger if I was first, they got into mine, and if Mr. Bray's was first, they got into his—there was no opposition offered by Bray's men, not pulling people away—I stopped at Regent-street, which is the usual place for stopping, and Bray stopped there—our other omuibus, the "Triumph," followed me three minutes behind—I did not see it, but that is the time—I stopped opposite Day and Martin's—there is a batter's shop only ten or twelve doors from Bray's stables—we have stopped there ever since the road has been estab<lb></lb>lished—Bray's still kept with us all the way to the Rank—It came in behind me—every omnibus is allowed three minutes there—he took a turn round Cornhill, and as I came from the corner of the Bank, he came from the corner of Cornhill at the same moment, and kept on with me in the same way, all the way up to Paddington—where I stopped, he stopped—John Lee was the driver—he had been in the service of Mr. Trevett—the conductor was <hi rend="italic">Jem</hi> Raines, I believe—I had not known him in any other character, but I heard he had been a fighting man—he had been a con<lb></lb>ductor before, I believe, but not employed by Mr. Trevett—I took my second journey at three minutes past twelve o'clock that day—Bray's, that went with me the first journey, went the second—he proceeded in the same way as he did on the first—we have regular customers that go by the omnibuses—we carry them one day, and perhaps not again for a week—we have not a regular body to ride down in the morning, and ride back again—I was followed all that journey just in the same way, by the same John Lee.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was there any expression besides having this <hi rend="italic">turn-up</hi> with the <hi rend="italic">old cobbler</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The first was, "We will give the old <hi rend="italic">snob</hi> a turn"—when we came from our third journey, we went to Mr. Trevett's stable, which is very nearly a quarter of a mile out of the road, and they followed us to the stable, huzzaing, and saying they would give the <hi rend="italic">old cobbler</hi> a turn as they passed by—they said they would <hi rend="italic">melt his wax</hi> before they had done with him—that was said so that any person who was standing on the ground might hear it—It was ballooed out from the top of their omnibus—they were hallooing out, "We will <hi rend="italic">melt</hi> the old cobbler's <hi rend="italic">wax</hi> before we have done with him"—that was in Market-street, where our stables are—we went there to take the horses home—they had no reason to go, for their horses stand in Holborn—I went home to tea in Star-street, and when I came back, Aaron Bray's omnibus was waiting at the public-house, near the corner of our yard, till we went out—when I got on the omnibus, I drove away, and they followed me directly—I went to the Wheatsheaf, to go the same journey again, and they pursued the same course again—I am positive as to their going on monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday; but they might omit one journey on Tuesday or Wednesday—they conducted their omnibus so as not to leave ours—I conducted mine at the usual pace to keep the time to a minute, as I did before—some time after this, one was taken away, but they kept on with us till the following Monday—they only went one journey on the Sunday, unless it was very late—not at my time,</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did one go away? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> One was taken away on Thursday, the 11th, but Jhon Lee remained—he worked in with me at my times, and also worked in at other times—sometimes he would go a little out of times, but three times a day he went with me, but it all depended upon whether he got any thing—he went three times with us, but if he did not get any thing, he might shift away</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210225"></xptr>
               <p>into other times—he might hang back a little—the omnibuses all stop at the Crown, and all start from the Wheatsheaf, unless they are a little too late, they all stop at the New Inn—they do not stop at the corner of Regent-street, but just traid along there—on the first morning, Bray got first to the Crown, and to the New Inn—I will not be positive which got first to Regent-street—we passed each other—If one stopped to take up a passenger, the other passed by—I never drove in oppositiom—I drove the regular omnibus—I heard that Raines had been a conductor before—my conductor was Dodd—he has been in Trevett's employ—I never heard that he had been a prize-fighter—I have been dirver to Mr. Trevett two years last May—I have kept the time I now keep for nine months—I never drove in opposition, but one day, that was the "Albion"—I do not recollect the number of it—It was against Mr. Bray.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you drove the "Albion" that day, what conduct was pursued by them or you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Ipursued the course that he had done to me before, retaliating—I waited at the Crown to see whether Mr. Bray's omnibus came to oppose Mr. Trevett's—It did come, and I went with it, and followed it—It he started and I started—he went first—Thomas Lee, his driver, gave me a challenge, and said, if he was <hi rend="italic">game</hi> to Woolwich, was I <hi rend="italic">game</hi> to follow him—I said, "I am <hi rend="italic">game</hi> to follow you wherever you like to go"—he did not go to Woolwhich, but he ran up and down the streets, and I followed him about, out of the regular track—there was no obstruction against me for three days—they never ran their pole against me, so that passengers could not get in—I never saw any thing of the sort.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> By whose orders did you do that? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Mr. Jhon Trevett told me I was to drive that omnibus that day, and that was all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1199" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1199" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1199" type="surname" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1199" type="given" value="AARON"></interp>AARON MARTIN</persName>
                  </hi>. In June last, I drove the "Triumph" omnibus, be<lb></lb>longing to Mr. Robert Trevett, from the Wheatsheaf to the Bank and back—I remember Mr. Bray's omnibuses starting on Whit-Monday—on that morning I saw them standing at the corner of New Church-street—we stand at the corner of Old Church-street, the Edgeware-road separates them—I pulled up at the corner of Old Church-street, and John Lee and Henry Maun, the drivers of Mr. Bray's <hi rend="italic">buses,</hi> said, "We have come to melt the <hi rend="italic">old cobbler's wax"</hi>—I started twenty-four minutes after nine o'clock, and Henry Mann started with me—we were in a line, he at the corner of New Church-street, and I at the corner of Old Church-street—when I stopped at the corner of Oxford-terrace, he stopped with me—when I stopped at the corner of Uxbridge-road, near the New Inn, (Where we stop,) he stopped exactly with me—my omnibus stood close to the curb, and he stopped right against me—when I stopped at the corner of Regent-street, he stopped with me—when Itook up a passenger, he passed me—when he took up one, I passed him—we went on to Day and Martin's—I pulled up on the near side of the road to the White Horse, No. 100, and he pulled up on the opposite side—he stopped near Bray's stables in coming up, he did not in going down—I went on to the Bank, and took my three minutes—he did not take any time, but went into Cornhill, and plied for passengers, and when I came off, he started and pulled against me down the Poultry—I went back as far as Day and Martin's—he there changed horses, and I lost him, and did mot have him any more—the second journey he went down with Mr. Cowderoy's <hi rend="italic">bus.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1200" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1200" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1200" type="surname" value="MARRS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1200" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MARRS</persName>
                  </hi>. I have been in the service of Mr. Trevett, as coachman, above two years—before Whit-Monday I drove up and down the New-road</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210226"></xptr>
               <p>I afterwards was appointed to drive the "Albion" by Mr. John Trevett—I always understood he had the sole management of the business—I began to drive on Whit-Monday, on account of Mr. Bray's omnibus coming, and waiting at the public-house till Mr. Trevett's came out, and then going with them—I saw that myself, as the omnibuses which go the New-road, and those which come down Oxford-street and Holborn, go the same way down part of the Edgeware-road—I saw Mr. Bray's omnibus, on Whit-Monday, come down to Mr. Trevett's stables, and wait there, which is out of the regular line of road, in Praed-street—I heard them say, they meant ruining the <hi rend="italic">old cobbler</hi> if they possibly could; that was the main ex<lb></lb>pression, they talked about <hi rend="italic">melting his wax</hi>, and other expressions—I began to drive on Whit-Monday—I observed Mr. Trevett's regular omnibuses on that day—when they started, Mr. Bray's started, and then I went as well—on the Tuesday I saw Mr. Bray opposite Day and Martin's—I heard him say, "I mean sticking to the <hi rend="italic">old cobbler</hi>, old Trevett, because his times are good ones"—I drove the whole of that week—sometimes I was first, sometimes Bray was—when I pulled up for a passenger, his driver would put his pole against my door, and not allow a passenger to get in—that was done half-a-hundred times, and more than that—they carried on the opposition to equally the same length that I did—their pole was put so as to obstruct my passengers—It was mpossible for them to get in; and if a passenger hailed me, they would run their pole against me—If the pas<lb></lb>sengers did not get out of the way, it would knock them down—I remem<lb></lb>ber, at Regent-street, there was a gentleman about to get into my omnibus, and John Lee prevented him, and he got a black eye from the conductor of my <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—Lee was preventing him from getting into my <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, by words, and by force as well—the gentleman had hailed me—I pulled up, and he was going to get into my <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, and they drove the pole right against the door—I pulled onh one side, and Lee followed the passenger, and pre<lb></lb>vented him getting into my omnibus by geting before him—he put out his arms, but did not lay hold of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BUMPUS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You drove along the New-road? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, till five o'clock on the Monday—I then had orders to go to the Wheat<lb></lb>sheaf; and if Mr. Bray's omnibus went with Mrs. Trevett's, I was to go on; if not, I was to return—I ran the whole of that week, when they ran against Mr. Trevett's—I did not follow them wherever they went—I only made one journey that night—I do not know that there was a time to spare that night—I do not know that there were three minutes, and only two omnibuses to run—I was sent out with that <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> to protect our other <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>; to go if they went, and to come back if they did not go with our <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> our usual regular omnibuses went the next morning, and I was there in waiting—If Mr. Bray's went with Mr. Trevett's, I was to go with him—I was an extra omnibus that morning—Mr. Bray's started, I started, and of course I went at the time of one of our other omnibuses—our first "Albion" started first—Mr. Bray followed him—then I followed, and then the "triumph;" and there was another of Mr. Bray's, behind the "Triumph"—Mr. Bray's was between the two "Albions" when he started—that continued a short distance down the Edgeware-road—we continued within a few yards of each other; some<lb></lb>times I was first, some times he was—willis drove the other "Albion"—we staid about the same length of time at Regent-street, and then went on abreast together—I cannot recollect who went first—my "Albion" was No. 177—I did not always drive at the same time that Bray's omnibus</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210227"></xptr>
               <p>did, all that first week, because, in some journeys, he did not go against Mr. Trerett's, and then I did not go with him—on the second day, Bray's omnibus went three journeys out of the five, at the same time that Mr. Trerett's did; and I did not go more than three journeys with him that day—I went with one of his omnibuses every day in that week—when I was driving on the New-road, I went from the Wheatsheaf; my first time was twelve minutes and a half past nine o'clock; the second, six minutes past twelve o'clock; and the third, about eight minutes before three o'clock—I went my third journey on that Monday—on the Tuesday I saw Robert Brayat Day and Martin's, about twenty-five minutes past one o'clock—I was driving the omnibus—he ws driving Aaron Bray's against me—I do not know his number—Willis was driving thr regular omnibus, the other "Albion"—I went to the Bank on Wednesday morning—Bray's omnibus took his time there—I do not know that he was summoned for it—I saw him take his time—he turned in; and the man that calls the time called his time, and he went.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1201" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1201" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1201" type="surname" value="MANN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1201" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY MANN</persName>
                  </hi>. I drove the omnibus that had "Aaron Bray" on the side of it—I drove it the first time it started out of Bray's yard—I had previously been occassionally employed by Mr. Trevett—there were two omnibuses started from Mr. Bray's yard on Whit-Monday—Mr. Bray was there when they started—he did not say how we were to drive on the first morning—we went up to Paddington—on the Tuesday morning Mr. Bray gave us directions to keep in the same time as we worked in the first day—(that was Trevett's time)—he did not mention any person's name—on the Thursday morning the conductor told me, while Mr. Bray on Tuesday was there, to stick to Bolton's time—I had told Mr. Bray on Tuesday that I had stock to Trevett's time all day long, on the Monday, and he told me to stict to him again, and he would have his horses ready to change—the om<lb></lb>nibus that I drove ran with Mr. Trevett's on the Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have been telling my friend a good deal of the instructions Mr. Bray gave you respecting Trevett—do you remember on the Thursday after you commenced, driving out of the regular line of road? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, we went up to Bolton's table, we <hi rend="italic">fetched</hi> one of his omnibuses out of the yard, and followed it—we went on in opposition to Trevett and Bolton about eight or nine days—after that I left Bray's service without notice—I remember after that I left him he called son horseback at the mews where I lived—I told him I had a summons to attend to—I had been summoned to Marlborough-street for one of my own men who drove a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi>—Bray then addressed himself to my conductor, and he offered Bray a shil<lb></lb>ling for the earnings of the omnibus, which was all he had got—Bray said, d—n the 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., it was not money he looked after, but the shabby way in which he left him, and if he got into any trouble he would see him out of it—I was discharged—I was foned 40<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., at High-street after I left Mr. Bray, for a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> of mine—I am quite sure it was by Mr. Bray's direction that I drove against Mr. Bolton—I did not notice who drove Mr. Bray's omnibus after I left.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BUMPUS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you driven for any of the defendants? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, <hi rend="italic">ne'er</hi> a one in the box—I have driven one or two journeys along the line of ropad for Goldburn, but I have never driven for Bolton since I left Mr. Bray, to the best of my recollection—I have been but about four journeys since I left Mr. Bray—I might probably</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210228"></xptr>
               <p>have gone one journey for Mr. Bolton—I believe that was the next Sun<lb></lb>day evening after I left Mr. Bray—I was here yesterday, waiting outside—I know the policeman Bates, No. 7—I saw him here yesterday—I am not held to bail in reapect of a man of the name of Goose—I am not under any bail—I have been before a Magistrate lately, on account of Mr. Goose; he swore his life against me, but the Magistrate would not believe him—I was not present when any body struck Bates yesterday—I never saw any body strike him—I was not present when bates struck any body—he pushed him out of the way—It was not because something was said about being a witness for the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1202" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1202" type="surname" value="GAMBLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1202" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH GAMBLE</persName>
                  </hi>. My father keeps the Fountain Abbey, Market-street, and I manage the business—It is the house to which Trevett's omni<lb></lb>bus drivers usually come. On Whit-Monday I was there, and two persons who did not usually come, came there with Mr. Bray's omnibus—I cannot say what they said they would do, but they had refreshment at our house—they asked for ten, and that not being ready, they called for apint of ale, and a <hi rend="italic">screw</hi> of tobacco—the tea was got ready for them—I brought it; while that was done, Trevett's omnibus started—they left their tea behind, and started off.</p>
               <p>---- <hi rend="smallCaps">DEDMAN</hi>. I live in Market-street, and am a piano-forte-maker, On Whit-Monday I went into the Fountain Abbey, a little before five o'clock—I saw Bray's omnibus stopping there—two of Bray's men called for tea—they called for ale, and while it was getting ready, I was sitting in the front parlout—the forms were out at the window—they saw Trevett's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> go, and they left their tea and went after it—I was there on the Wednesday—I saw Bray's omnibus in Market-street—It passed Mr. Trevett's stable—the men were huzzaing and said, "You are not <hi rend="italic">game</hi> to follow us"—and "We will run the b—y <hi rend="italic">cobbler</hi> down" or "off"—I have seen Brauy's omnibus occasionally, and observed its proceedings—when people were going into Trevett's omnibus, the conductor of Bray's omnibus has got down from Bray's and laid hold of the people that were going into Trevett's—I have seen that several times—I have seen nothing else done ij particular—as it regards one running before tha other, that has been a common thing—some<lb></lb>times Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> before the "Emperor," sometimes the "Emperor" be<lb></lb>fore that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When was it you saw the con<lb></lb>ductor of Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> pull a passenger from Trevett's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot say the day—It was in the Edgeware-road—It might be four or five days after the starting—It might be eight—It was between two and five o'clock in the afternoon when I saw this, as that is the only time that I have an opportu<lb></lb>nity or witnessing their conduct, my employment being at my father's in Marylebone-street, and I go to my dinner for two hours—I do not know who was the driver or the conductor of Trevett's omnibus—I think the name "Albion" was on it—I cannot say whether the "Emperor" omnibus was there—I did not see any omnibus beside "Albion", and Mr. Bray's—Mr. Trevett's was first—Bray's conductor got down from the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, and en<lb></lb>deavoured to prevail on the people to get into his <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—he laid hold of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it a man or a woman? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have seen him take both.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> But on this particular time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not say any particular time; as I stated before, it was five, or six, or eight days after they began the running.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it a man or a woman upon that occasion? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I saw him take both.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210229"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you sober now? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, Sir—I cannot say any particular day that this took place—I told you that before, but it was at the time I am in the habit of being in the Edgeware-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you see them on the Wednesday? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About five o'clock—one of them was then driving past Mr. Trevett's—there were se<lb></lb>veral persons visiting at Mr. Trevett's; persons belonging to the yard—I think it was as near five o'clock as could be—that is the time they come in to have their tea—Trevett's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> was in, and Bray's drove round, and came past.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1203" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1203" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1203" type="surname" value="BATES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1203" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES BATES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a City police-sergeant No 7. On Whit-Monday I was on duty in Cheapside, the Poultry, Lombard-street, Cornhill, and round the Bank—I do not recollect any particular dat that I observed Trevett's or Bray's omnibuses, but within a few days of Whit-Monday, see<lb></lb>ing there were two new omnibuses, I took notice of them—they tried to take their time at the Bank—I receive orders at the Bank, that if there are any new ones, not to allow them to pull in at the Bank till they had permission, I believe from the Ward authorities.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did you observe Bray's omnibuses do? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They tried to pull in—I remonstrated with them, and told them they must not do so till they had been before the Police Committee—I remonstrated with the driver the first day, and on the second day of his starting I believe Mr. Bray came down himself—I told him my instructions were not to suffer him to pull in, till he had been before the committee—he insisted upon pulling in, and the time keeper told him also that he could not—he in<lb></lb>sisted upon doing it, and I believe the time-keeper summoned him on the following Saturday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was the effect of Bray's omnibuses trying to pull in upon the other omnibuses? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It caused a great deal of confusion—by direction of the Bank there are three allowed to stand on the stand at one time, and only two during the payment of dividends; consequently, if there are more than three coms on, we order the last one off—Bray's happened to be the last on several occasions, and we ordered him off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Supposing he had been the first, would he have been ordered off then? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, Sir; the first week he would have been ordered off, but after that he got permission.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> On any occasion when any of Mr. Bray's omnibuses were there, did you hear any thing respecting Mr. Trevett's? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I heard various conversations among the man—they said, "We intend to run with you", meaning the drivers of Mr. Trevett's—"We are going to <hi rend="italic">melt the old cobbler's wax</hi> now"—"He shall not have it all his own way, and we will let him know it"—I have heard Bray's omnibus drivers say that to Trevett's—Colson, the time-keeper, was there at the time, and I believe Budd was there—the time-keeper summoned Bray's driver for obstruction—after the first week they were allowed to follow the omnibus out that they had followed in but sometimes they would not wait—the men would leave the omnibus and go away to get their refreshments—from my observation, they appeared to run against Trevett's omnibus, and they did that for some time after they had permission to take time—I once had occasion to lay hold of Bray's horses—I was coming from Threadneedle-street one Friday evening, and Mr. Bray was being remonstrated with—he would not come in behind—he insisted on cutting in, and I laid hold of his horses and backed them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see Bray's come with or behind any other omnibus besides Trevett's? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, with several of them that have been</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210230"></xptr>
               <p>down first in the morning—I have seen one of Bray's run against Bolton's—they all conducted themsoleves pretty much alike—I complained before the Police-committee that Bray's did not conduct themselves fairly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you remember being at the White Lion, on the evening of the 27th of July? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I know the house, but I never was in it in my life—I backed Bray's horses once, his omnibes was half across the road—I think on that occasion the two ominbuses that were in, were Mr. Bird's—they stood one behind another, and Mr. Bray's wanted to come in between them—young Mr. Bray was driving—I did not see the "Albion" or the "Emperor" at that time, they were not in Bank-street, they might he in Pinees-street—this was about half-past six o'clock in the evening—It might be three weeks or a month after Bray came ont he road—when Bray's omnibuses came in, they were generally in company with the "Emperor" and the "Albion"—the "Emperor" was generally before Bray, and the "Albion" behind—the omnibuses of all the defendants came in that direction—I have seven six or seven of them come in that way—I never went to Mr. Bray's, passengers, and told them it was dangerous for them to go in—I said to young Mr. Bray, the day after the sale, "I thought you sold off yesterday, and had done with it," and he went and reported it to his father, who brought me up for defamation—the Magistrate dismissed it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1204" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1204" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1204" type="surname" value="GYNN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1204" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN GYNN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City police-constable No.</hi>13.) I am stationed round the Bank. I remember when Bray's omnibuses first made their apperance—they appeared to me to be running direct against Trevett's—I saw Mr. Braw and his men frequently—I have heard the man say to Trevett's men that they would <hi rend="italic">melt the old cobber's wax</hi>—they would say to them, "We will be with you, you b—s," and use very bad language; and somtimes they made use of the word snob—I do not know that they talked of any body else beside Trevett—this violent opposition went on, I should think, about a week—Bray's omnibuses did not take their time, and take their turn as the others, when they first started—they afterwards had time given them—they did not keep their time as other omnibuses did—they used to come in, and go round Cornbill, and ply for hire, if they could get passengers; if they did not, they wanted to come in and take time—that occasioned a disturb<lb></lb>ance, because they would want to <hi rend="italic">cut in</hi> betwixt the three omnibuses which were allowed to stand at the Bank—I have found it necessary to interface, by their coming in irregularly, wanting to <hi rend="italic">cut in,</hi> and throw the others out, which almost endangered the people's lives, by thowing omnibuses and horses on the pavement—they have come in at times and taken their times regularly; at other times they have not—they have gone out in all kind of ways; at other times taking times—they have gone to the corner of Cornbill, and stood there—I have crossed over to tell them to go on—one Friday evening, about two months ago, Mr. Bray's omnibus had been playing round Cornbill; hethen came and wanted to go in between the first and second omnibuses which were standing there—I spoke to Mr. Bray, and said, "Why don't you wait till the first is gone, and then come in third?"—he theb said, "I will be d—d if I don't get them all turned away from the Bank, if it costs me five hundred pounds, and I will line the street with omnibuses. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1205" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1205" type="surname" value="PARISH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1205" type="given" value="PHILIP"></interp>PHILIP PARISH</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City police-constable No.</hi>45.) I remember Bray's omnibuses coming to the Bank about Whit-Monday—they principally came in Trevett's time—I did not see what their conduct was at the Bank, as my duty is in the Poultry and Mansion House-street—I remember a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210231"></xptr>
               <p>one time, walking up the Poultry with old Mr. Bray, five or six weeks after his omnibuses came—he had spoken about an officer who had been so kind as to assist him in getting up a horse, and had said to him, "Mr. Bray, you are very nervous; get on one side;" and he said he should give him a sovereign, if he might—I said he might—he said he would ask leave, and I belive he did—the sovereign was given, and divided between myself and others—I said to him, "You must be very uncomfortable in driving in opposition in this way: you can't expect these men to give their bread away without trouble"—I told him I thought he would be much more confortable if he had purchased one of their times, as they had purechesed them before—he said, "We should have shown them better"(or something of that)"if Alexander had not deserted me"—(we had before had notice that there were six omni<lb></lb>buses coming down)—he said he should have been very well if Alexander had not put him in the hole, as Alexander had promised to start with him, and then they should have made the Paddington masters look about them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you seen him running in Mr. Bolton's time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> yes. <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you observed him going in other masters' times? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you observed him going in other masters' times? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, he has sent out an omnibuses with others—If one goes out, and has not got further then Queen-street, another will follow him—I have seen op<lb></lb>position several times, and if the opposition that has received three mi<lb></lb>nutes comes out, and only gets as far as Bucklersbury, the other that comes behind him goes before him—I have seen one omnibus with the name of "Corbett," following Mr. Bray's the others have gone in their regular turn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1206" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1206" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1206" type="surname" value="CORNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1206" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS CORNEY ESQ</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Deputy of Broad-street ward. The Bank is situated there—I can hardly say that it is left to me to settle the times of the omnibuses there, but I generally do—the officers of the ward seem to be under my direction—I wrote a circular letter to the omnibus pro<lb></lb>pritores in 1833, in consequence of the great confusion at the Bank, and the Governor of the Bank having written to me that he should put the Bank Act in force; I saw him, and told him I would enter upon it, and make some arrangement, which I did—I was instructed by the police committee to make some arrangements, that times might be set by the proprietors, and kept by the time-keepers—I invited the proprietors to meet me, to make some arrangements which I prescribed; one was, that no longer should any <hi rend="italic">cabs</hi> be allowed there, as we found a great many robberies took place, and there were thieves taking advantage and robbing the public—the officers were ordered to remove any persons of that description—a few of the par<lb></lb>ties met me, but by no means half their number—Mr. Shillibeer was then in opposition with them, not subscribing properly to their funds—I could not get them to terms but by threatening to put the Bank Act in force—they said, if I could get the twenty-nine proprietors to agree to having fifty-nine omnibuses, they would be satisfied, if I pointed out an offi<lb></lb>cer in whom the ward would have confidence—one was appointed, who was to pay no respect to any one, but to summon every person who did not keep his three minutes—that went on for some time, till Mr. Bray began to make a disturbance, and threatened that he would continue it—he said it to me, I belive—I summoned him before the police-com<lb></lb>mittee—he said that he should not belong to their committee—he would run his omnibus and take time, and I had him summoned before the police-committee—he had not had time then, our officers being strictly</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210232"></xptr>
               <p>bound by the list they had, they could not give him a time, without putting some one out; and in trying to take time, he had caused the obstruction—I could not give him time then; he must have had the concurrence of the committee, as after the arrangement had been made, it was final—after this, Mr. Bray applied to me, and I told him I had ceased then to interfere, the Police-committee of Aldermen not being uniform in their decrees—a worthy Alderman assumed, that this was a monopoly, and therefore he would not sanction any list—I said, "As I formed this list by the wish of a former committee if this court, and you won't sanction it, I will have nothing more to do with it"—before this there had been tolerable order at the Bank—I had no complaints, and if they had not been tolerably well conducted I should have heard—there was good order kept generally, as long as that list was observed—I did not hear of any time being allotted to Mr. Bray, as I ceased after the first list—If he has been admitted, it is in the new list—I know Budd, the time-keeper.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is this a copy of the letter you sent to the pro<lb></lb>prietors? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; it was addressed to all the proprietors—I do not know whether Mr. Bird attended the meeting or no—these are the printed regu<lb></lb>lations—they were calculated, in my judgment, to benefit the public, and the proprietors also—these regulations were mine; whethere they have acted upon them all, I cannot say.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BODKIN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> After the agreements were made, I think some per<lb></lb>sons were summoned before the Police-committee? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; for obstruc<lb></lb>tions—the regulations were never binding upon the Police-committee, but the persons were summoned for attempting to break the regulations which the Paddington proprietors had formed—they were convicted in 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. each, or imprisoned—the Magistrates of London have convicted persons for causing obstructions, which would not have been caused if the regu<lb></lb>lations had been attended to.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BUMPUS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Bray call on you, and ask for a time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I cannot say when, I think it was within the last six or eight months.</p>
               <p>A <hi rend="smallCaps">JUROR</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> If I understand you rightly, no person can start an omnibus without entering into this arrangement, the times being filled up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I imagine they must make an arrangement to take some time, or else cause an obstruction.</p>
