                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1207" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1207" type="surname" value="BUDD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1207" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BUDD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am time-keeper of the omnibuses at the Bank, and was so last Whit-Monday. On that day I observed two of Bray's omni<lb></lb>buses come up—they came in with Mr. Robert Trevett's—I believe it was between ten and eleven o'clock—I was desired to tell them that they were not to take time at the Bank, that was the order of Mr. Corney—I told them so—It was the order that no other omnibuses were to take time, but the 55 which I have on my list—they worked out—they did not come on the stand the first time—they went up Cornhill, and down by the Rank—when the time came for Trevett's to start, I saw Bray's go out with them—one of Bray's conductors said, he would have time, in spite of the <hi rend="italic">cobbler</hi>—they seemed to be waiting to go with Mr. Trevett—they continued to come to the Bank, three or four times a day—Bary afterwards applied to the proper authorities, and got his time—he then took his time, following out the omnibuses that he followed in—that was the order of Mr. Theobalds, the marshal—I think that was about a fortnight after—It was after the 13th, but I do not know what day—I cannot call to my recollection after whose omnibus Bray took his time—sometimes he came and took</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210233"></xptr>
               <p>time, and sometimes he did not—he waited for passengers—that was after he got permission to take time—when he did not take time, he went up Cornhill, round Bank-street, playingmfor passengers, and sometimes he went and waited down Princes-street, before he came to take time—after Bray had got time, there were two omnibuses behind him, but the hind ones are not allowed to solicit passengers, while the first one is there—there were three omnibuses, including Bray's—It is not allowed in the City for the two to apply for passengers, whilst the first is on—that is the agree<lb></lb>ment of the proprietors—they have no connexion with the City authorities—they have nothing to do with our regulations.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> After Bray's omnibuses ceased to run in Trevett's time, who did they run against? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They ran in Trevett's time for three or four days, and about three days after that they ran in Mr. Bolton's time, for three or four days.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it found that these regulations were calcu<lb></lb>lated to promote the convenience of the public? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not a doubt of it, Sir, we should do nothing without it—we should be all in conflusion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Mr. Bray communicate with you on the subject? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you not a police-officer, and sworn in for the purpose of keeping these regulations in force? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I was—I was sworn in before Sir Peter Laurie, Lord Mayor—I have the date of the month here—we have had oppositions from Mr. Shillibeer and Newman, and then Mr. Bray came—I have only been there two years—one of Bray's omnibuses ran against Bolton—he commenced by running against Trevett, and then against Bolton, and then against Richard Bird and Johnson—I never saw Mr. Bray till that day—I receive 25<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week by the hands of Nathaniel Colaon—he is the relieving time-keeper—he is a peace<lb></lb>officer—I have observed the omnibuses belonging to the two Bird's, Cow<lb></lb>deroy, and Johnson—I have seen Bray's omnibuses drive very steadily from the bank—I am stationed at the Bank—three minutes is the regula<lb></lb>tion time—they do not stop a longer period.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Suppose a driver came and wanted to take refresh<lb></lb>ment, might he not do that before he comes on the stand? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was not three minutes the time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I have summoned only our own omnibuses, and they were fined 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., because they would not go when I have told them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Mr. Bray ran his omnibuses without regard to time, just as he pleased? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; there was no regular time—he came when he thought proper—he has run against them all nearly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BUMPUS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You are paid by the proprietors, were you named originally by the proprietors? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I know nothing of the proprietors—I was engaged by Mr. Corney, and paid since by the proprietors, by the hand of Mr. Colson—I am the regular time-keeper at the Bank—Mr. Colson relieves me—when I am not there, he is—when Bray came, on the very first time, on the Monday morning, he tried to take his time at the Bank—he said he should have time—he went up Cornhill—he did not come back in Cowderoy's time that day—I cannot recollect whethere he did the next day—he came once or twice in Bird's time; I think, not so soon as that week; it was about nine days after—he might have come on in their time that week, while I was relieved, for two hours—I remember the "Emperor" and the "Albion" being put on—they came and took time—I have seen the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> with "Sylvester" on it</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210234"></xptr>
               <p>come about the third day—they name on, and <hi rend="italic">timed</hi> themselves off, and tock no account of it—sometime they came on as it suited their purpose; and sometimes they did not—I took no account of it, till I was ordered by Mr. Theobalds—they then took their time—that was Mr. Bray's omnibas—we have a variety of "Emperors"—that was put on againts Bray, with "Sylvester" on it, has come on once I belivee, and taken time, but not more to my knowledge—I believe the "Albion" took time once—they came once, to my knowledge, to the Bank, without taking time—they used to go out with Aaron Bray on other occasions, and I took no account of them, when they worked out odd; that has nothing to do with me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have been asked whether on the first or second or third day, you did not observe Bray's omnibus going in cowderiy's time; did he appear to you to be going more against Travett's time than any other? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The first two or three days he did—at the time that Bray came on, there were fifty-five omnibuses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have been asked whether you did not observe one omnibus come out, and wait in Princes-street, and of the ownern till Bray came there to run against Trevett, in the first instance? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Cer<lb></lb>tainly not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was there an omnibus called the "Tally-Ho?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That was before the 10th of November—there has been no opposition since, but by Mr. Blower—his is an odd <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>—he takes his time regularly at the Bank, following out the <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> that he follows in, and that is the regulation in the City, or else we should all be in confusion—I can' tell when Blower had his time—my fellow time-keeper can tell that—I mean the same Robert Belower, who has been called—he does not take regular time—he goes when it suits him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> That is, when he comes in, you order him to go at his time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He does not always come in, and take time—he goes up Bank street, and takes passengers—If a person comes in and takes time I can only insist that he should set off at his regular time—If a man comes in to oppose the regular omnibuses, and remains at the Bank for the time specified he must go—he is liable to be punished under the Bank Act—If he goes when I direct him, he must run against one of the regular omnibuses, which causes so much confusion and obstruction, even on the paverment.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> If an opposition omnibus, not coming in and taking the regular times, thinks fit to come for instance at twelve o'clock, must he not beces sarily oppose himself to one of the omnibuses running at that hour? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; and by that means he creates confusion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The times are regulated by the proprietors? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; there are twenty-two to fill these times—If two more came on it would not only create oppostion, but confusion—If the time was made two minutesit would be no use it would not pay them—we have had very great complaints of so many omnibuses being in the City—If the other omnibuses were as well regulated as ours are, there would not be so much confusion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1208" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1208" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1208" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1208" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am employed by the inspector of stage coaches, at Somerset House.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210235"></xptr>
               <p>I take my stand between St. Paul's and Cornhill, at eight o'clock in the morining—my business is to observe the stage coaches that pass, and omnibuses likewise, to cheek the Somerset House returns—I stop till twelve o'clock at night—I have frequently observed Bray's omnibuses for the last three months—I have seen Bray's, Corbett's, and Silvester's coming one against the other—Bray's generally after the other—young Bray has driven his omnibus up, and by placing the pole against the door, prevented passeners getting in—that was a common thing—on one occasion, I observed Raines, one of the conductors, when young Bray derove up get, down when a lady was on the pavement, come and take a child out of her arms, and put it in thje omnibus while the lady was calling on the paverment—when persons have been calling they have been pulled about by different conductors, by Trecett and others, and Bray—they taken hold of people and said, "This is my <hi rend="italic">bus,</hi> I am first"—when the people have been going to get into the "Em<lb></lb>peror", that being generally first, the passagers would be pulled about by Bray's conductors: and the same conduct was pursued towards the "Albion" by each of Bray's omnibuses—both of the conductors were pugilists, Raines and Mann—sometimes Mann used to drive, and some<lb></lb>times conduct—I know nothing of him myself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know that Rsines has been a pugilist? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It has been advartised—I do not know any other conductors pugilists—Murphy has been a pugilist, I have heard—I have heard of Savage—I do not know him—I know the driver of the "Emperor"—I have not been on the box of the "Emperor" when it has been going out of its way after Bray's—I have been on the box twice—I have not followed Bray's omnibus out of the road—I have gone all the way up to Paddington on the box of the "Emperor"—I have gone to Madia-hill upon that very omnibus, when it went out of its regular road to a public-house where they dine—I did not see Bray go there—I saw him before me part of the way—he was there—he dined there—young Bray did—It is about six pr seven weeks sinve I saw the lady with the child—I do not know the name of the public-house—the omnibuses was in the yard—the horses were in the stable—It was near Bray's stable—the "Emperor" did not wait till Bray's went—the "Emperor" started first—I did not see Bray's going just before us.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What took you there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had been to Mr. Burn, a tailor, at Paddington—I went to Maida-hill for a ride.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How far was your tailor's from the house where you dined? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not a quarter of a mile—they went down I do not know how many back streets—I came back by the same omnibus—I am authourised under the commissioners of the Stamps, by Mr. Lewis Levy—I make my return to him—they go to Somereset-house—my appointment is to inspect the numbers of stage-coaches and omnibuses that pass through cheapside between eight in the morning and twelve at nignt—I am appointed by Mr. Lewis Levy, who is authorizeds by the commissioners of stamps to appoint who he thinks proper.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long was it after Bray's omnibus ran, that you went to Maida-hill? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Eight or nine weeks.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1209" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1209" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1209" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1209" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MILLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am time-keeper at the wheatsheaf, Edgeware-road, and was so last Whit-Monday. I recollect Bray's omnibus coming out—I cannot say the day—I did not seee Trevatt's omnibus the same day Bray came out—I have repeatedly seen them together—they were trying, of course all to get passengers—first one and them another, and each of them probably in their turns obstrueting the way—I have seen Bray drive his pole against the others, so as to prevent passengers from getting in—he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210236"></xptr>
               <p>has waited a quarter of an hour, backing his omnibus against the pavement—I have seen Bray's prevent passengers getting into the others, by pulling close to the omnibus door—I cannot charge my memory whether I have heard Bray's men make use of any particular expressions.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you recollect Bray's first starting? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I re<lb></lb>collect their first starting—I have not seen them coming across Paddington Green—I have seen them coming from Bolton's yard, in Church-street—I will not be certain whether I saw any of Bray's drive close to the door of Bolton's omnibus—I do not think I have seen any thing of this—I have seen Bray obstructing any omnibuses that were coming on—he has omnibuses—the pole might probably be over the pavement, which would obstruct passenger from getting in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1210" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1210" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1210" type="surname" value="COLSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1210" type="given" value="NATHANIEL"></interp>NATHANIEL COLSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am time-keeper at the New Inn, Edgeware-road. I remember Bray's omnibuses coming out last Whit-Monday—they passed the New Inn to go towards Paddington—I Observed them back—the regular omnibus was standing at the New Inn, that was one of Mr. Trevett's—Bray pulled up ten or twenty yards opposite—not quite so for ward—when Trevett started, Bray started directly and went with him—he appeared to be running to get the roas against Trevett's <hi rend="italic">bus,</hi> if possible; they would get the ground where Trevett usually stood—I have seen Bray's people pulling the people in, trying to get there into the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, from Trevett's or any <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> that might be there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1211" type="witnessName">
