                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1211" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1211" type="given" value="JACOB"></interp>JACOB MILLER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant E</hi> 3.) I have been on duty in Oxford-street and Holborn for the last three months—I have observed Bray's omnibus going along—three were running together, Bolton's, Bray's, and I believe Trevett's but I am not certain—I mean the "Albion" and "Em<lb></lb>peror"—I have seen persons hail the "Albion" and I have seen Bray's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> draw up to the door of the "Albion, "—I should think that prevented pas<lb></lb>sengers getting in—I have seen Bray's men soliciting passengers from the "Emperor"—there never was a nuisance before Mr. Bray came up—I have threatened to take some of them into custody—I have been threatened to have my head <hi rend="italic">punched</hi> by Bray's conductors.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was that when the "Albion" was before and the "Emperor" behind? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; they were all stopped toge<lb></lb>ther—It was Bray's men I was going to take up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1212" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1212" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1212" type="surname" value="TYRRELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1212" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD TYRRELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I have been on duty in Oxford-street and Holborn for the last three years—I have observed Bray's omnibus going along—I have observed Trevett's, but I cannot speak with certainty about them—I have noticed Bray's going along, one before and one behind the other omnibuses—on one occasion I noticed the driver Mann, run against the other omnibus—there seemed to be oppo<lb></lb>sition, one as bad as the other—on two occasions I have summoned Bray's omnibus for misconduct, such as obstructing—he was once fined 40<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the other time he had to pay costs—I have observed Bray's men abuse the passengers of the others, using blackguard language to the passengers or the coachman; that was Mann—the abuse was mutual, equal on both sides.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> At the time you had Bray up were there not four other omnibuses, and did not you have them all up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There were six. I only had Bray up, his <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> had the name large on it—the other names were small—I did not observe the names on them—I told Mr. Bray if he employed such men to drive, the lives of people were in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210237"></xptr>
               <p>danger at all times, because they were improper persons—there might have been some opposition before, but it did not come under my observa<lb></lb>tion—we only had Mr. Bray himself up the second time—he was ordered off by one of our men, and he would not leave.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have, under the Police Act, authority to order these men off? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Certainly; it was for abuse and refusing to go off—It was waiting for one of the others to come up to run agianst it—once there were six together; and when he was summoned on the other occasion he was on a different road, where he had no business to be—the objection was made that he was not plying for hire, but for opposition—before this opposition came on the omnibuses ran perfectly regular—there have been running from Paddington to the Bank as many omnibuses as could be ocnsistent with public convenience and safety.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1213" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1213" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1213" type="surname" value="TRINGHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1213" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS TRINGHAM</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable T</hi> 137.) I was on duty at the Wheatsheaf last Whit Monday, and saw Bray's omnibus there, and Tre<lb></lb>vett's—I have seen Bray, when there have been two standing there accord<lb></lb>ing to the regulations, pull in both behind and before the others; and have seen them very frequently crossing each other in going down the Edgeware-road, preventing passengers going in—I have seen them draw the pole of their <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> across the other regular <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>, and prevent passengers going in on several occasions—I have seen Bray's men soliciting passengers from other omnibuses—I have had occasion to remonstrate with them at the Wheatsheaf—I have told them I must summon them—I have summoned them for furious driving.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you seen Bray's omnibus do any thing to Bol<lb></lb>ton's <hi rend="italic">bus</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; drive the pole right across the door, and prevent pas<lb></lb>sengers going in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What are your instructions? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> To let only two wait there at a time, and those to start every three minutes—I have seen Bray's omnibus come before and behind them—I have seen them stand on the opposite side of the street, at the corner of Cross-street, but very seldom—I have seen the other omnibuses cross Bray's, but I have not seen the others drive up their poles to prevent pas<lb></lb>sengers getting into Bray's—the others were the "Emperor" and "Albion," and sometimes other <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>—I summoned Bray once for furious driving, but Bolton was not summoned at that time—Bray was driving furiously down Edgeware-road—the "Albion" was driving against him at that time, and the "Nelson," whcih belongs to Mr. Hill—the other was Bar<lb></lb>dell's—I summoned those three, and they were all fined 40<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. each.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1214" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1214" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1214" type="surname" value="FELTHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1214" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FELTHAM</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a polic-inspector. I am stationed at Paddington—the Edgeware-road comes under my notice—my attention has been directed to the Wheatsheaf—I remember Bray's first starting—I think it was about Whitsuntide, all was then quiet—as soon as Mr. Bray's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> began to run, there was a great opposition—I should say he opposed the whole of them—I cannot say whose time he ran in—I am acquainted with their times—there was the "Emperor" and "Albion," two <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>—they went with him or he with them; that caused confusion in the road—I have repeat<lb></lb>edly observed Bray's omnibuses drive close up to either of the others—I have seen them come out from Portman-market, perhaps up Church-street, down to the Wheatsheaf—and Bray ran before them or behind them, so as to obstruct people from getting in—I have seen the same at the New Inn, and the half distance, the "Crown"—I have never paid particular attention to</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210238"></xptr>
               <p>what they said—they have been summoned for furious driving, and wilful misbehaviour in the Edgeware-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The "Emperor" and "Albion" were with him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; they were summoned at the same time, on the 25th of June, and fined.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1215" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1215" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1215" type="surname" value="COLSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1215" type="given" value="RICHARD NATHANIEL"></interp>RICHARD NATHANIEL COLSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I have had some conversation with Aaron Bray respecting his running his omnibus—he said that unless he could receive 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from the proprietors, he would indict them all for a con<lb></lb>spiracy, and ruin them—I remember two of Trevett's men being in custody—Bray said he had been as good as his word—It was not the men he wished to hurt, but their masters, as he could get nothing out of the men.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You are one of the time-keep<lb></lb>ers? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I am at all the parts in the course of the day—I pay the other time<lb></lb>keepers—I go from one place to another through the day—I receive the money to pay, from the conductors of the respective omnibuses—I know Mr. New<lb></lb>ell—I have not rendered accounts to him latterly—I did some time since—I think the last was six or seven months since—It was the account of what money I received, and what I paid at the time-keepers—I did not account with him as the secretary—I did not know he was secretary—I accounted to him for all the money I received from the conductors, and for all I paid—I never received money from him to make up any deficiency—I have paid trifling sums to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you subpœnaed as a witness by the prosecu<lb></lb>tor? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I was—I was not called.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I suppose you are subpœnaed on the other side too? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I am subpœnaed by the attorney for some of the defendants—I have paid occasional surpluses to Mr. Newell, and I have done so to Mr. Bol<lb></lb>ton since, from the time I ceased to account with Newell—I received two shillings and sixpence from the conductors for each omnibus—that is supposing they all pay regularly on Saturday evening—sometimes they do not pay regularly—then it is the middle of the next week before I re<lb></lb>ceive their money—I received half-a-crown from each—It amounts to about 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and if this has not been all paid to the time-keep<lb></lb>ers, I pay the overplus to Mr. Bolton—I pay them 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week—I re<lb></lb>collect Mr. Bray's omnibus coming on—Johnson has put on an additional omnibus since then, and so has Pearce—I do not recollect that Newell has—Mrs. Watson has—Bolton has put on two omnibuses since, and Trevett, and Cowderoy, and Pearce—the first remark that Bray made, in reference to his omnibuses, was very soon after they started, in Holborn, I think within a week, it was near his own premises, where his omnibuses were in the habit of stopping to change horses—I think there were several people there—there was generally a crowd round his omnibus—the second conversation was on the morning that two of the defendants were taken into custody on this indictment—It was on a Wednesday, the 22nd of June or July—I have a memorandum of the date—Mr. Bray came up to me when the officer signified to the driver and conductor of the omnibus that he wished to take them into custody, that they were his prisoners—he said, "I am very sorry for you, young men; I have no enmity against you, it is not the men, it is the masters I want, I can make nothing of them; the law must take its course;" he concluded by saying," If they will give me 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. I will stop all these proceedings, and take away my omnibus "—that is all I can recollect—there were not many days between the first and last</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210239"></xptr>
               <p>conversations—I cannot say to a day or two—It was not many days—the first conversation was in the street, where his omnibus was stopping, near his own yard in Holborn—the last conversation was when the men were taken—the first conversation was in Holborn also, at the same place—I never saw Bray any where but close to his own premises—his yard is within a hundred yards of the starting place—Mr. Bray was in the habit of going to the place where the omnibus starts from, and he was there—I do not recollect who else was there—there were always people round his omni<lb></lb>bus—the "Emperor" and "Albion" were not always before and behind him when they stopped there—I do not recollect whether they were there at the time this conversation took place—there must have been passers-by within ten yards of us—our own omnibuses were there, and the drivers and conductors—I cannot tell what drivers or conductors they were—It was not said loud enough to be heard—It was addressed to me—I should say, it was not loud enough to be heard by people a few yards distant—he was standing by my side—he was waiting there before the defendants came down—there were several people there on this occassion, but not in hearing—he began the first conversation in the usual way, with respect to his omnibuses running—he said he would have his time, and his omnibus should run, in spite of all the opposition of the other omnibuses running against him; and if the proprietors chose to give him 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., he would take his omnibus off altogether—that is all he said that I can recollect—this took place at the first conversation, but he had said something to me previous to this.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he, in a conversation after the indictment had been found, say he had been as good as his word? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I understood that to refer to what he said in the previous conversation—In the first con<lb></lb>versation he said he would indict them all for a conspiracy, and ruin them all, unless he received 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KNOWLES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have stated that Mr. Pearce has put an omni<lb></lb>bus on the road since; does that go at its regular time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many have you now? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Those that run regularly, and work at three minutes, amount to fifty-five.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KNOWLES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many had Pearce on the road before Bray? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two following each other, and one working at another period—the new one fell into the time of the two—the three did not go exactly in six mi<lb></lb>nutes—the two that followed him and the other worked in twelve minutes—the five worked in twelve minutes—the time before allotted to four—they went at regular times—Mr. Bray did not go at regular times—the new one could not have been in opposition to Bray.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have stated three minutes to each one? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—Pearce and the two before him had twelve minutes for the four; and when he came with the new one, there were five—then, instead of their staying three minutes, they staid two minutes and a fraction—Bray never applied to have any time, only at the Bank—young Bray never asked me to call times for him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1216" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1216" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1216" type="surname" value="LEE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1216" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN LEE</persName>
                  </hi>. I was a driver in the employ of Aaron Bray. I started with one of his omnibuses on Whit-Monday—he told us to do as we thought proper—we started from Holborn to Paddington, to the Wheat<lb></lb>sheaf—we then turned round and went to the City with Trevett's omni<lb></lb>buses, because it was a good time—we picked up five or six passengers, which Trevett's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> would have had if we had not—we started first—Trevett's yard is in Praed-street—we followed his omnibuses there—his</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210240"></xptr>
               <p>omnibuses went into the yard, and then we stopped at the public-house opposite till they came out again—that is out of the line of road from Pad<lb></lb>dington to the Bank—Mr. Bray has seen us on the line of road, when we were running against Trevett—for some time we ran against Trevett and Bolton—we ran against Trevett six or seven days, and, off and on, against Bolton—Bird's omnibus was on the road—Mr. Bray directed me to run against Bird and Johnson and to leave them till furthur orders, and we continued to do so six or seven days, and I was then taken ill.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you receive directions from Mr. Bray to run against Trevett? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Then your master, the first day, told you he left it to you to drive against who you liked? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, to do as we thought proper—I never received instructions to drive against Trevett; but I did to run tin Bird and Johnson's time—that was about a fortnight afterwards—the "Albion" and "Emperor" were on the road at that time, I believe—I molested them at times before they started one be<lb></lb>fore and one behind—I endeavoured to get all the passengers I could against them—I have not been driving for Johnson since—I drove for one of his men—I have been driving for Turnbull since.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> How long have you been driving for Johnson's men? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two or three journeys.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say the first day you ran against Trevett? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I do not recollect that I told Mr. Bray of it—I do not recollect that he asked me against whom I ran.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What means did you take to molest the other om<lb></lb>nibuses, beside picking up passengers? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Sometimes I gallopped by them, trotted by them as they stopped to pick up passengers; and when I stop<lb></lb>ped they came past me—when they have stopped for passengers sometimes I have pulled the pole against the door, and would not let the passengers get in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you instructions from Mr. Bray to do so? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you instructions from him to do exactly as you liked? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When was it you began to pull the pole against their omni<lb></lb>bus first? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In two or three days after they began running—I did that to do the best I could for my employer—I pulled the pole first against them—I did so because I thought I was doing the best I could to get pas<lb></lb>sengers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1217" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1217" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1217" type="surname" value="BIRBECK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1217" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BIRBECK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a time-keeper in Bartholomew-lane. I have seen Mr. Bray's pmnibus twice, and have seen Lee driving it—on the 20th of June I was going through the Poultry—I observed two omnibuses going together—I saw a lady wishing to get into the first—the one behind drove the pole agains the door, so as to prevent the lady getting in—I cannot tell who drove the one behind, but the name of Aaron Bray was on it—the omnibus drove on about three yards—the pole was again driven against the door, and she went away—there is a house in Bargholomew-lane where Trevett's men stop to get drink—I saw one omnibus with the name of "Corbett" on it, and one with "Aaron Bray" on it, stop there when he stopped, and went on when he went on.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you not one day ordered out by the officers? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I was subpœnaed the day before yes<lb></lb>terday—I was here the first day, and then I was subpœnaed—Mr. Goodge acted as time-keeper in the New-road in my absence—I attend there from nine in the morning till nine at night—Corbett's was the "Albion"—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210241"></xptr>
               <p>did not see the "Emperor"—the "Albion" Went first each time, and Bray's after it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1218" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1218" type="surname" value="EDMONDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1218" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY EDMONDS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an oil and colourman, and live in the Edge<lb></lb>ware road, and Drury-lane. I remember riding outside the omnibus called the "Emperor," on the Monday after Whit-Monday—It was driven by a man named Sylvester—I got up at Paddington—I observed an omnibus of Aaron Bray's, with its pole close to the door—that was at the end of Farringdon-street—a man of the name of <hi rend="italic">Cuddy</hi> Mann was driving—he drove against the hroses, and knocked them down, I walked on some time, and then they got up—I was then frightened at being outside, and went inside—the manner in which the omnibus of Aaron Bray had acted, frightened me—the pole was so close, that the passengers could not get in, and they would not go in either of the <hi rend="italic">buses.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you a proprietor? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I have got a sum of money lent to two omnibuses in the New-road, called the "Rose," but I am not a proprietor—I have no share in them—one formerly belonged to my father—one belongs to my brother, and the other to Meredith—my name is on it, but it is obliterated, and has never appeared—It was covered before it came out of the painter's loft—I have only an interest in the two "Roses," and one without the name at all, which belongs to Meredith—I do not know whether Meredith is connected with the defendants on the New-road—I am bail for Richard Carpenter, one of the defendants, not for any of the others—I am in the habit of riding from Paddington to my other shop, two or three times a-day—this was the second week that the omnibus started, called "Aaron Bray"—I cannot tell whether the "Albion" was there—I did not see it, but I have seen the omnibus of Braw go to fetch the "Albion" out of the stable—there were several of Mr. Bolton's there at the time I was riding.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Which omnibus did you see go to fetch the "Al<lb></lb>bion?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two of Aaron's <hi rend="italic">buses</hi>, one round at the end, the other square.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to lend money on these omnibuses? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There was a widow of the same name as myself in difficulty, her husband died—I lend a little money, till it came to 300<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I was compelled to take these omnibuses, and a man of the name of Lyons, whom Mr. Norton knows very well, contrived to do the widow out of one of them—I have always understood that Lyons and Nortons were related, and I was afraid to <hi rend="italic">tackle</hi> them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did they go to fetch the other omnibus? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The second Monday after they started.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1219" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1219" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1219" type="surname" value="BARDELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1219" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BARDELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a veterinary surgeon. I am brother of the two defendants who have been acquitted—I know Aaron Bray—I went to him to inquire why he had put my brothers in the indictment—he told me my brothers must be in indictment, but he should offer no evidence against them, as they were always more friendly to him; but they must be in the indictment, as his attor<lb></lb>ney had told him so—In consequence of that conversaion, I made an appointment with him to meet him at Mr. Norton's chambers, and I did meet him there on the Sunday—I saw Mr. Norton—I asked Mr. Norton in Mr. Bray's presence, why he advised my two brothers to be put in the indictment—Mr. Norton said, "Bardell, it is hardly fair that you should be here, but I will tell you—Mr. Bray has told me, that he has no evidence to offer against your brothers, but Mr. Bray com<lb></lb>missioned your brother to ask the proprietors of the Paddington committee for 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to go off the road;" and Norton said, "If we do not include your</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210242"></xptr>
               <p>brothers in the indictment, the Paddington proprietors will subpœna them against us, and that would tell very materially against them"—I am posi<lb></lb>tive Mr. Norton said that, and in Aaron Bray's presence; and he said, if the proprietors did not give Mr. Bray 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or take his stock at a valua<lb></lb>tion, and give him 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., that he would suffer to have his arms and legs cut off, if he would not ruin them—I was to tell my brothers, and they would know what they had to depend upon—Mr. Norton said, the people they intended chiefly to offer evidence against, was Mr. Bolton, and Trevett, and they would go in his times—I walked out of the office, and Mr. Bray walked with me—he said "I told you I would be as good as my word, I have met you at Mr. Norton's, and he has told you the reason of your brothers being in the indictment, and unless they give me the 100<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., I shall go on. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You were bail for your brothers? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; the only reason why I went to Norton's to ask why my brothers were in the indictment was because I had not put in bail at that time—It was last Sunday monthly, I think—I bailed my brothers on the Monday, and this conversation took place on the Sunday—I have given all that took place as near as I can recollect—I did not do to him about the bail—I had no occasion to say a word about it—my bail had not been re<lb></lb>fused before this Sunday—on the Saturday before I went to Maryle<lb></lb>bone office Smith my father, with a view, if my brothers wanted bail, to bail them—when I got there, Mr. Norton, and my brothers were in con<lb></lb>versation—he said to my brothers, "We will put the thing off till Monday," and my brother said to me, "John, I shall not want bail to<lb></lb>day, will you bail me on Monday?" and I told him I would—I never want into the office—I was told in the street by my brothers, that it would not be wanted till Monday, and I went on Monday, and it was taken directly—o Sunday, Norton said, "We are willing to take yours and your father's bail on Monday, but it will come to nothing about them"—he said "Your brothers must be in the indictment, and they must bail it, as the rest have done"—they did not mention any names—my father and mine were the names tendered on Saturday, and we were the bail on Monday—I went there in my chaise—I drove young Bray there, and met his father in his chaise there—I waited till he came—old Bray and I went into Mr. Norton's office, and young bray went in the chaise—he came into the office once while we were there—I was there perhaps altogether about an hour and a half, waiting about—old Brag, Mr. Norton, and myself were present when this conversation took place—I do not know whether young Bray was there—I do not remem<lb></lb>ber it—I was to tell my brothers what their decision was, to have the money, or the things sold off—I was to tell the proprietors and my brothers together—we were not in the office an hour and a half—we were waiting some time for Mr. Bray; but it was said, I do not recollect whether at the beginning, middle, or end—I did not tell Mr. Norton I had been to the office the day before, to give bail; but he saw me there, and I saw him—he did not tell me I had not given notice—I did not know it, till I asked the question at Mr. Norton's, whether my brothers were to be indicted' for if they were not indicted, they would not require bail—I did not mention any thing about bail—the conversation com<lb></lb>menced with Mr. Norton—Mr. Bray and him had some conversation—Mr. Norton said they would be indicted, and he had a reason for it—I am quite sure he told me that my brothers must be in the indictment—my brother told me he was indicted—I did not know they were indicted—I went to know whether they could not be exempt—Mr. Bray said they</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210243"></xptr>
               <p>could not; and I went to ascertain the cause why they must be in it; and Mr. Norton said, they must be indicted—old Bray might not have been in the office the whole time—he is troubled with the rheumatism, and in a great deal of pain—he was walking about the room and passage, and sat down to rest himself—I do not know how much of the time he was out of the office—we had some conversation, and I came out; and Mr. Bray told me what Mr. Norton had said—he told me, "John, you see I am as good as my word; I said I would bring you down to Mr. Norton, to know why your brothers were in the indictment, and he has told you; I did commission your brothers to see the Paddington committee; and I must have a hundred pounds and times, or your brothers must be in the indictment, or they would be subpœnaed by the proprietors to give evi<lb></lb>dence"—Mr. Bray was in and out of the room, when Mr. Norton told me what I have stated—I do not know whether he was near enough to hear—he was walking about the room—I put in bail on Monday—I do not know whether my brothers were members of the committee—I know nothing about it—It is out of my business altogether—I told my brothers this message; and I have told one or two of the proprietors since, when I have seen them—I did not go to Paddington to see them—I had nothing to do with the meeting of the proprietors—I know nothing about it—I have one place in Gloucester-mews, and one in Rathbone-place.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you known Aaron Bray some time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he has known me, and has had oppurtunities of seeing the way in which I have conducted myself through life.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1220" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1220" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1220" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1220" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WRIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a grocer, and live at the corner of Rath<lb></lb>bone-place, Oxford-street. I have been in the habit, before and sinse the 8th of June, of observing the conduct of the omnibuses coming up and down Oxford-street—before Aaron Bray commenced, the omnibuses were perfectly quiet—they would stop at my door and put down, and do every thing quiet—after Bray came, there has been a con<lb></lb>stant confusion—If an omnibus belonging to one of the proprietors drew up, Bray would drive up very fast behind them, or come in front of them—If an omnibus were to stop, Bray would stop—he would always wait for the other—there appeared no object for him to stop, but he always did stop—when the others have stopped to take up passengers, or set them down, Bray has always stopped, whether he had any one to take up or not—I have observed this conduct for four or five months—I am not interested for either of the proprietors—I have come forward without being subpœnaed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1221" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1221" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1221" type="surname" value="MOORE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1221" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD MOORE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an undertaker, and live in Rathbone-place, close to Oxford-street, the door is at the corner—I have had my attention called to the omnibuses, going from Paddington to the Bank, up and down Oxford-street, and I have observed the conduct of Mr. Aaron Bray's—the omnibuses were going regularly before he came—after he came, when the omnibuses drew up, Mr. Aaron Bray's drew across them, and prevented the passengers going in them—that has been, if not from the first, very soon after—I observed it in June—I have observed this conduct of Bray's more than twenty times—If Bray has been on the right side, he has tried to come in between them and the pavement—at other times he has gone and drawn across the crossing, to prevent the passengers getting in—I have no interest whatever in the issue of this inquiry—I came without any subpœna.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many omnibuses have you</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210244"></xptr>
               <p>seen with Mr. Bray's? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have seen one or two—I did not notice their names—I have seen two frequently, and whenever an omnibus came down the street, Mr. Brays, omnibus would come, and run across it—I have seen the "Emperor"—I cannot swear whether I have seen the "Albion"—I have seen another—I have only observed that when another omnibus has drawn to the side of the street, Mr. Bray has done the same—I have not seen the others do the same to Mr. Bray—I will not swear that I saw Mr. Bray's before the 15th of June.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Bray appear to be the aggressor? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; by con<lb></lb>stantly crossing over to them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1222" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1222" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1222" type="surname" value="MASON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1222" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH MASON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a chemist, and live at No, 26, Oxford-street, I have had opportunities of observing the conduct of the omnibuses—I have seen Bray's drive as rapid a pace as the others—If one of the others stopped, Bray's would stop also—I have seen that more than once or twice, and I have seen them run the pole very near the other people's door—he has not stopped for a passenger—I have not had that idea—I have not seen any passengers—when the others went on, Bray did so also, and followed them up or down the street, keeping very near indeed to them, as near as they could—I observed that in the first month—I should say Bray's was the aggressor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you have seen Bray's did you see it with others? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; the "Emperor"—I cannot state any others, but I have seen it with two or three others.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it following them or before them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They were altogether.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did those other omnibuses appear to you to act towards Bray, as Bray did to them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should say there was no difference in that respect.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you subpœnaed here? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I am here quite dis<lb></lb>interestedly—It was intimated to me a friend of the parties that Mr. Holding wished me to come, but I should have come without.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who is Mr. Holding? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He was a very respectable che<lb></lb>mist in the same shop—I heave no motive in giving evidence but to clicit the truth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1223" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1223" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1223" type="surname" value="WILLIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1223" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WILLIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a hosier, and live at No. 371, Oxford-street. I have had opportunities of observing the omnibuses that drive up and down from paddington to the Bank for the last five years—those with "Aaron Bray" on them have been conducted in the most did orderly way imaginable—previous to the omnibuses of Aaron Bray coming on the road, they were conducted as orderly as it was possible for vehicles of that description to be; so much so, that I allowed them, two years ago, to change horses at my house—since Aaron Bray began running up the street, to my coat, I have found that the disorder has been so great that ladies could not come in their carriages to my shop—they were afraid—I have seen the other omnibuses stop to take up passengers on several occasions—I have seen Bray's omnibuses pull up with the pole against the door of the other omni<lb></lb>buses, to prevent a passenger from getting in, in more instances than one—from what I have seen, Bray was decidedly the aggressor, because I con<lb></lb>sidered he was in opposition to the others—before Bray came, the road was orderly—they were going quitely about their business.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SERGEANT BOMPAS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When this took place, was the "Emperor" the one before or behind it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> That I could not say; but I have noticed Mr. Bray's being a blue omnibus.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> During the time you have paid attention to these omni<lb></lb>buses, upon your oath, have you seen any difference in the conduct of the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210245"></xptr>
               <p>other omnibuses towards Bray's, or have been nearly the same? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have noticed that when another omnibus has been going down the street quietly, Mr. Bray's has driven up as near to them as possible—I have not seen the others serve Bray so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1224" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1224" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1224" type="surname" value="GRAPE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1224" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES GRAPE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a wine and spirit merchant, and live at No. 412, Oxford-street, I have observed the omnibuses drive up and down from Paddington to the Bank—I have had frequent opportunities of observing the conduct of the drivers—the conducting of the omnibuses before Bray's came on, was upon a very excellent principle, and since that, they have been a great annoyance to the passengers—I have had occasion to ride down to the City, having a nervous debility, and have been annoyed by Mr. Aaron Bray's omnibus coming close to the one I wished to get into—I think that Bray's omnibuses were the aggressors.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Why do you think they were the aggressors? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Because I have seen the others drive to get a-bead get ahead of the others—I have never seen the others drive to get a-head of them. not when I have been fiding in them—I have seen the omnibuses driving past each other—I have seen two or three omnibuses with Bray's—I think I can swear I have not seen so many as five—I will go as far as two or three—I will not go farther—I have not noticed the names of the omnibuses—there are so many passing and re passing; but I noticed Bray's, because there are only two of them, and I suppose there are thirty others—Bray's always seemed to be driving up to the spot where I live—they came on the road, in my opinion, to oppose others—I have noticed them more particularly—they did not drive up to my house, but nearly so; within twenty yards or so—they all stop there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you have seen them, was the conduct you complain of, the conduct of Bray's omnibuses? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350921-name-1225" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1225" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1225" type="surname" value="KENDALL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350921-name-1225" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES KENDALL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a victualler, and live in Rathbone-place. I have noticed the omnibuses that go along Oxford-street repeatedly—I have observed Bray's omnibuses—when I have been riding in another, they have repeatedly crossed the front of the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> that I was riding on, and pulled up by the side of it or behind it; that has caused a great annoyance, so far, that I felt inclined to get off the one I was on—our omnibus went on the same as usual—I felt annoyed by those <hi rend="italic">buses</hi> con<lb></lb>stantly drawing up infront of the <hi rend="italic">bus</hi> I was on—I do not know that the rest of the passengers did—Bray's pulled up in the usual way of pulling up—I did not observe that they did it to take up a passenger—I cannot say what reason they had for pulling up, but they did pull up—I did not see them take up passengers when they pulled up.</p>
               <p>----<hi rend="smallCaps">MUNDAY</hi>. I live at No. 20, Harrow-road. I am conductor to Mr. Richard Bird, and have been so seven or eight months—I recollect the time of Bray's omnibus coming on—It was in the Whitsun-week—I have observed the conduct of Bray's to my master, because he was driver to the one that I was conductor to—they have told him they would not leave him—they meant to stick to his times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WHITEHEAD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What had he said to them before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> My master said to young Bray, "What do you come in my</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183509210246"></xptr>
               <p>time for? it is very hard to come against a poor man getting his living"—he made answer, "We mean to stick to you, we fancy you. "</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">T. Bolton</hi> and <hi rend="italic">R. Trevett</hi>—<rs id="t18350921-2116-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
